We don't open
for half an hour!

257
00:12:39,047 --> 00:12:40,799
Open the door, please.
Just open the door.

258
00:12:40,847 --> 00:12:41,757
It's important.

259
00:12:41,807 --> 00:12:43,638
L-I'm sorry, we don't open
for half an hour.

260
00:12:43,687 --> 00:12:44,722
What's your name, ma'am?

261
00:12:44,767 --> 00:12:45,836
Darcy.

262
00:12:45,887 --> 00:12:46,922
Darcy. That's a pretty name.

263
00:12:46,967 --> 00:12:48,605
I'm in a bit of a fix.
I need a suit for my kid.

264
00:12:48,647 --> 00:12:49,557
This is my son Frank.

265
00:12:49,607 --> 00:12:50,517
Oh, hi.

266
00:12:50,567 --> 00:12:51,477
He needs a black suit.

267
00:12:51,527 --> 00:12:52,846
Black suit...

268
00:12:52,887 --> 00:12:54,161
There was a death in the family.

269
00:12:54,207 --> 00:12:55,606
My father, 85 years old,
war hero.

270
00:12:55,647 --> 00:12:57,524
Yeah?

271
00:12:57,567 --> 00:13:00,206
There's a funeral
this afternoon, military funeral

272
00:13:00,247 --> 00:13:02,283
planes flying overhead,
21-gun salute.

273
00:13:02,327 --> 00:13:03,555
Geez.

274
00:13:03,607 --> 00:13:06,485
Frank needs to borrow a suit
for a couple of hours.

275
00:13:06,527 --> 00:13:09,405
I'm sorry, we don't loan suits,
and we're not open.

276
00:13:09,447 --> 00:13:10,721
Darcy... Darcy, please.

277
00:13:10,767 --> 00:13:12,564
- (<i>sighs</i>)
- Come back.

278
00:13:12,607 --> 00:13:14,598
Darcy... is this yours?

279
00:13:14,647 --> 00:13:16,365
(<i>jingles</i>)

280
00:13:20,087 --> 00:13:22,681
I just found it
in the parking lot.

281
00:13:22,727 --> 00:13:24,763
Uh-huh.

282
00:13:24,807 --> 00:13:27,037
It must've slipped
right off your neck.

283
00:13:28,847 --> 00:13:29,757
(<i>tires screeching</i>)

284
00:13:29,807 --> 00:13:31,718
Don't hit the curb.

285
00:13:33,967 --> 00:13:35,525
(<i>brakes squeaking</i>)

286
00:13:36,527 --> 00:13:38,279
Now get out,
walk around the back

287
00:13:38,327 --> 00:13:39,999
and hold the door open for me.

288
00:13:42,687 --> 00:13:44,598
(<i>car horn honks</i>)

289
00:13:49,127 --> 00:13:50,276
All right.

290
00:13:50,327 --> 00:13:51,476
What's next?

291
00:13:51,527 --> 00:13:52,846
Okay, stop grinning.

292
00:13:52,887 --> 00:13:56,118
When I get inside, you go back
to the front seat and wait.

293
00:13:56,167 --> 00:13:58,556
Even if a cop comes
and writes you a ticket

294
00:13:58,607 --> 00:14:00,563
you don't move the car,
understood?

295
00:14:00,607 --> 00:14:02,404
Dad, wha-what's all this for?

296
00:14:02,447 --> 00:14:04,403
You know why the Yankees
always win, Frank?

297
00:14:04,447 --> 00:14:06,005
'Cause they have Mickey Mantle?

298
00:14:06,047 --> 00:14:07,639
No, it's 'cause the other teams

299
00:14:07,687 --> 00:14:09,996
can't stop staring
at those damn pinstripes.

300
00:14:10,047 --> 00:14:11,002
Watch this.

301
00:14:11,047 --> 00:14:12,844
The manager
of Chase Manhattan Bank

302
00:14:12,887 --> 00:14:17,085
is about to open the door
for your father.

303
00:14:18,687 --> 00:14:20,962
Mr. Abagnale, um

304
00:14:21,007 --> 00:14:22,998
we don't usually
loan money to people

305
00:14:23,047 --> 00:14:25,322
who have unresolved business
with the IRS.

306
00:14:25,367 --> 00:14:27,085
That's a misunderstanding.

307
00:14:27,127 --> 00:14:28,719
I hired the wrong guy
to do my books.

308
00:14:28,767 --> 00:14:30,405
A mistake, I...
anybody could make it.

309
00:14:30,447 --> 00:14:32,642
I just need you guys
to help me weather the storm.

310
00:14:32,687 --> 00:14:36,965
Sir, you're being investigated
by the government for tax fraud.

311
00:14:37,007 --> 00:14:38,998
My store is a landmark
in New Rochelle.

312
00:14:39,047 --> 00:14:40,878
I have customers
all over New York.

313
00:14:40,927 --> 00:14:43,395
Well, you're not a customer
at Chase Manhattan.

314
00:14:43,447 --> 00:14:44,436
We don't know you.

315
00:14:44,487 --> 00:14:46,159
I'm sure your bank
in New Rochelle

316
00:14:46,207 --> 00:14:48,163
they know you,
they could help you out.

317
00:14:48,207 --> 00:14:49,686
My bank went out of business.

318
00:14:49,727 --> 00:14:52,036
Banks like this one put
them out of business.

319
00:14:52,087 --> 00:14:54,123
Now, I know I made a mistake,
I admit that

320
00:14:54,167 --> 00:14:55,520
but these people want blood.

321
00:14:55,567 --> 00:14:56,477
They want my store.

322
00:14:56,527 --> 00:14:58,324
They've threatened
to put me in jail.

323
00:14:58,367 --> 00:14:59,925
(<i>stammers</i>)

324
00:14:59,967 --> 00:15:01,400
This is America, right?

325
00:15:01,447 --> 00:15:02,436
I'm not a criminal.

326
00:15:02,487 --> 00:15:03,920
I'm a Medal of Honor winner

327
00:15:03,967 --> 00:15:06,606
a lifetime member
of the New Rochelle Rotary Club.

328
00:15:06,647 --> 00:15:09,480
All I'm asking is for you
to help me beat these guys.

329
00:15:09,527 --> 00:15:11,916
It's not a question
of winning and losing.

330
00:15:11,967 --> 00:15:13,400
It's a question of risk.

331
00:15:13,447 --> 00:15:16,007
You're the largest bank
in the world.

332
00:15:16,047 --> 00:15:17,526
Where's the fu...

333
00:15:17,567 --> 00:15:20,206
Whe... Where's the risk?

334
00:15:25,127 --> 00:15:27,960
Dad, how could you just let him
take our car like that?

335
00:15:28,007 --> 00:15:29,918
He didn't take anything.
We took him.

336
00:15:29,967 --> 00:15:31,036
He overpaid by $500.

337
00:15:31,087 --> 00:15:34,204
Come on, Frank.

338
00:15:34,247 --> 00:15:35,600
Let's return the suit.

339
00:15:35,647 --> 00:15:37,558
(<i>Paula sobbing</i>)

340
00:15:43,167 --> 00:15:44,566
This place is good.

341
00:15:44,607 --> 00:15:46,438
It's small but, you know

342
00:15:46,487 --> 00:15:48,921
it's going to be
a lot less work.

343
00:15:48,967 --> 00:15:50,446
A lot less work for you.

344
00:15:50,487 --> 00:15:53,126
(<i>jackhammer drilling</i>
<i>in distance</i>)

345
00:16:01,207 --> 00:16:02,879
(<i>keys clank</i>)

346
00:16:12,687 --> 00:16:13,915
FRANK:
Hey, Dad.

347
00:16:13,967 --> 00:16:15,878
Hi.

348
00:16:19,287 --> 00:16:21,243
Where's your mother?

349
00:16:21,287 --> 00:16:22,356
I don't know.

350
00:16:22,407 --> 00:16:26,639
She said something
about going to look for a job.

351
00:16:27,927 --> 00:16:28,996
What's she gonna be

352
00:16:29,047 --> 00:16:30,878
a shoe salesman
at a centipede farm?

353
00:16:30,927 --> 00:16:32,042
(<i>laughing</i>)

354
00:16:32,087 --> 00:16:34,885
(<i>both laughing</i>)

355
00:16:36,767 --> 00:16:38,166
What are you doing?

356
00:16:38,207 --> 00:16:39,686
(<i>both laughing</i>)

357
00:16:39,727 --> 00:16:41,877
You want some pancakes?

358
00:16:41,927 --> 00:16:42,837
For dinner?

359
00:16:42,887 --> 00:16:44,684
On my son's 16th birthday?

360
00:16:44,727 --> 00:16:46,718
We're not gonna eat pancakes.

361
00:16:49,207 --> 00:16:51,675
Come on, why are you looking
at me like that?

362
00:16:51,727 --> 00:16:52,921
You thought I forgot?

363
00:16:52,967 --> 00:16:55,845
- I didn't think you forgot.
- I opened a checking account

364
00:16:55,887 --> 00:16:57,559
in your name.

365
00:16:57,607 --> 00:16:58,926
I put $25 in the account

366
00:16:58,967 --> 00:17:00,685
so you can buy
whatever you want.

367
00:17:00,727 --> 00:17:01,955
Don't tell your mother.

368
00:17:02,007 --> 00:17:02,996
I won't.

369
00:17:03,047 --> 00:17:04,082
Thanks, Dad.

370
00:17:04,127 --> 00:17:05,116
Yep.

371
00:17:05,167 --> 00:17:08,079
Didn't that bank turn you down
for a loan, though?

372
00:17:08,127 --> 00:17:09,719
Yes, they all turned me down.

373
00:17:09,767 --> 00:17:11,041
(<i>chuckles</i>)

374
00:17:11,087 --> 00:17:13,237
Then why you opening
a banking account with them?

375
00:17:13,287 --> 00:17:15,437
Well, because one day,
you'll want something

376
00:17:15,487 --> 00:17:17,284
from these people...
a house, a car.

377
00:17:17,327 --> 00:17:20,205
They have all the money.

378
00:17:22,847 --> 00:17:25,600
There's 50 checks there, Frank

379
00:17:25,647 --> 00:17:30,004
which means, from this day on...

380
00:17:30,047 --> 00:17:32,117
you're in their little club.

381
00:17:32,167 --> 00:17:35,477
I'm in their little club.

382
00:17:35,527 --> 00:17:37,518
You got that, you got it all.

383
00:17:37,567 --> 00:17:41,719
It's even got my name there,
huh?

384
00:17:41,767 --> 00:17:43,041
To the moon.

385
00:17:43,087 --> 00:17:47,842
- To the moon!
- To the moon.

386
00:17:48,087 --> 00:17:49,805
(<i>bells tolling</i>)

387
00:17:55,847 --> 00:17:58,600
See that? It's just a school.

388
00:17:58,647 --> 00:18:00,285
No different than Westbourne.

389
00:18:00,327 --> 00:18:03,956
Ma... you said you were
going to quit.

390
00:18:07,007 --> 00:18:10,317
Frankie, you don't have
to wear the uniform here.

391
00:18:10,367 --> 00:18:13,200
Why don't you take off
your jacket?

392
00:18:13,247 --> 00:18:16,080
I'm used to it.

393
00:18:16,127 --> 00:18:18,038
(<i>indistinct conversation</i>)

394
00:18:20,367 --> 00:18:21,402
Excuse me.

395
00:18:21,447 --> 00:18:22,357
Oh, yes?

396
00:18:22,407 --> 00:18:24,204
Do you know
where room 17 French is?

397
00:18:24,247 --> 00:18:25,885
GIRL:
Yeah, it's...

398
00:18:25,927 --> 00:18:27,645
(<i>snickering</i>)

399
00:18:31,447 --> 00:18:33,802
(<i>school bell ringing</i>)

400
00:18:33,847 --> 00:18:35,644
BOY:
But you frickin' killed him.

401
00:18:35,687 --> 00:18:38,997
(<i>loud indistinct conversation</i>)

402
00:18:39,047 --> 00:18:41,038
You selling encyclopedias?

403
00:18:41,087 --> 00:18:44,443
Yeah, he looks like
a substitute teacher.

404
00:18:51,927 --> 00:18:54,361
(<i>boy laughing</i>)

405
00:18:54,407 --> 00:18:58,605
(<i>loud conversation</i>
<i>and laughter continues</i>)

406
00:18:58,647 --> 00:19:00,683
Quiet down, people!

407
00:19:00,727 --> 00:19:02,922
My name is Mr. Abagnale!

408
00:19:02,967 --> 00:19:06,004
That's Abagnale, not Abagnahlee

409
00:19:06,047 --> 00:19:09,323
not Abagnaylee, but Abagnale!

410
00:19:09,367 --> 00:19:11,437
Now, somebody please tell me
where you left off

411
00:19:11,487 --> 00:19:13,398
in your textbooks.

412
00:19:14,807 --> 00:19:16,445
Excuse me, people,
if I need to ask again

413
00:19:16,487 --> 00:19:18,045
I'm going to write up
the entire class.

414
00:19:18,087 --> 00:19:20,317
Take your seats!

415
00:19:24,287 --> 00:19:25,800
Chapter seven.

416
00:19:25,847 --> 00:19:28,122
Will you please open your
textbooks to, uh, chapter eight

417
00:19:28,167 --> 00:19:30,681
and we'll get started?

418
00:19:30,727 --> 00:19:32,126
Excuse me,
what's your name?

419
00:19:32,167 --> 00:19:33,236
Brad.

420
00:19:33,287 --> 00:19:36,404
Brad, why don't you get up here
in front of the class here

421
00:19:36,447 --> 00:19:39,484
and read conversation
number five?

422
00:19:42,127 --> 00:19:44,766
(<i>pronouncing poorly</i>):
<i>"Les Francais sonts</i>

423
00:19:44,807 --> 00:19:46,684
<i>"uh, generalement</i>

424
00:19:46,727 --> 00:19:49,400
<i>- "dans leur pais que...</i>
- (<i>students laughing</i>)

425
00:19:49,447 --> 00:19:52,166
<i>Presque tout le monde</i>
<i>a cette impression..."</i>

426
00:19:52,207 --> 00:19:53,526
They sent for me.

427
00:19:53,567 --> 00:19:56,639
They said they needed a sub
for Roberta.

428
00:19:56,687 --> 00:19:59,360
I came all the way
from-from Dixon.

429
00:19:59,407 --> 00:20:01,477
Well, uh,
I always sub for Roberta.

430
00:20:01,527 --> 00:20:03,483
Excuse me,
why aren't you reading?

431
00:20:03,527 --> 00:20:04,676
(<i>continues reading</i>)

432
00:20:04,727 --> 00:20:07,321
I'll never come back to-to
Bellarmine Jefferson again!

433
00:20:07,367 --> 00:20:09,801
- You tell them not to call me!
- (<i>students laughing</i>)

434
00:20:09,847 --> 00:20:12,122
What do they think,
it's easy for a woman my age

435
00:20:12,167 --> 00:20:14,158
and all the money that it costs
to travel?

436
00:20:14,207 --> 00:20:15,925
I tell you,
they don't give a damn.

437
00:20:15,967 --> 00:20:17,241
(<i>students laughing</i>)

438
00:20:17,287 --> 00:20:18,640
Mr. And Mrs. Abagnale

439
00:20:18,687 --> 00:20:21,804
this is not a question
of your son's attendance.

440
00:20:21,847 --> 00:20:24,839
I regret to inform you that,
for the past week

441
00:20:24,887 --> 00:20:28,357
Frank has been teaching
Mrs. Glasser's French class.

442
00:20:29,647 --> 00:20:30,875
He what?

443
00:20:30,927 --> 00:20:34,840
Your son has been pretending
to be a substitute teacher

444
00:20:34,887 --> 00:20:39,005
lecturing the students,
uh, giving out homework.

445
00:20:39,047 --> 00:20:42,437
Mrs. Glasser has been ill
and there was

446
00:20:42,487 --> 00:20:45,320
some confusion
with the real sub.

447
00:20:45,367 --> 00:20:48,677
Your son held a teacher-parent
conference yesterday

448
00:20:48,727 --> 00:20:51,036
and was planning
a class field trip

449
00:20:51,087 --> 00:20:53,476
to a French bread factory
in Trenton.

450
00:20:53,527 --> 00:20:56,963
Do you see the problem we have?

451
00:20:57,007 --> 00:20:58,884
- Mrs. Davenport?
- Yeah.

452
00:20:58,927 --> 00:21:01,282
Uh, I have a note to miss fifth
and sixth period today.

453
00:21:01,327 --> 00:21:02,237
Doctor's appointment.

454
00:21:02,287 --> 00:21:04,278
- One moment.
- (<i>phone ringing</i>)

455
00:21:04,327 --> 00:21:05,555
I'll be right with you.

456
00:21:05,607 --> 00:21:06,517
(<i>whispering</i>):
Hey...

457
00:21:06,567 --> 00:21:07,477
MRS. DAVENPORT:
Yes?

458
00:21:07,527 --> 00:21:08,676
You should fold it.

459
00:21:08,727 --> 00:21:09,716
What?

460
00:21:09,767 --> 00:21:11,325
That note. It's a fake, right?

461
00:21:11,367 --> 00:21:12,595
You should fold it.

462
00:21:12,647 --> 00:21:14,319
It's... It's a note from my mom.

463
00:21:14,367 --> 00:21:16,005
I have a doctor's appointment.

464
00:21:16,047 --> 00:21:18,766
Yeah, but there's no crease
in the paper.

465
00:21:18,807 --> 00:21:20,763
When your mom hands you a note
to miss school

466
00:21:20,807 --> 00:21:22,399
the first thing you do is,
you fold it

467
00:21:22,447 --> 00:21:23,800
and you put it in your pocket.

468
00:21:23,847 --> 00:21:26,884
I mean, if it's real,
where's the crease?

469
00:21:31,407 --> 00:21:33,318
- (<i>school bell ringing</i>)
- (<i>door opens</i>)

470
00:21:36,247 --> 00:21:37,521
(<i>quietly</i>):
Frankie.

471
00:21:47,927 --> 00:21:50,999
(<i>both chuckling quietly</i>)

472
00:21:52,447 --> 00:21:54,324
Ma, I'm home.

473
00:21:54,367 --> 00:21:56,323
(<i>romantic music</i>
<i>plays on record player</i>)

474
00:21:56,367 --> 00:21:58,244
Oh, you remember
that girl Joanna

475
00:21:58,287 --> 00:22:00,357
I was telling you about?

476
00:22:00,407 --> 00:22:03,365
I asked her out today.

477
00:22:03,407 --> 00:22:05,602
Think we're going to go
to the Junior Prom.

478
00:22:05,647 --> 00:22:07,524
(<i>record scratches,</i>
<i>music stops</i>)

479
00:22:07,567 --> 00:22:09,319
Ma, is this
my driver's license?

480
00:22:09,367 --> 00:22:11,085
That's all there is,
two bedrooms.

481
00:22:11,127 --> 00:22:13,357
Oh, Frankie.

482
00:22:13,407 --> 00:22:15,238
You remember Dad's friend?

483
00:22:15,287 --> 00:22:17,084
Jack Barnes?

484
00:22:17,127 --> 00:22:18,355
From the club.

485
00:22:18,407 --> 00:22:19,362
Hello.

486
00:22:19,407 --> 00:22:21,238
He came by looking
for your father.

487
00:22:21,287 --> 00:22:23,881
I was giving him
a tour of the apartment.

488
00:22:23,927 --> 00:22:26,839
It's very, uh, uh,
spacious, Paula.

489
00:22:32,167 --> 00:22:34,317
Dad's at the store.

490
00:22:34,367 --> 00:22:37,200
So, Frank...
you're getting to look

491
00:22:37,247 --> 00:22:40,000
more like your old man
every day.

492
00:22:42,567 --> 00:22:44,842
Thanks for the sandwich, Paula.

493
00:22:44,887 --> 00:22:46,605
I'll see you later, eh?

494
00:22:46,647 --> 00:22:48,558
Wait.

495
00:22:52,487 --> 00:22:54,523
Is this yours?

496
00:22:54,567 --> 00:22:57,206
Oh.

497
00:22:57,247 --> 00:22:58,805
Well, thanks, Frank.

498
00:22:58,847 --> 00:23:01,077
Uh, that's the President's pin.

499
00:23:01,127 --> 00:23:03,436
I'd be in deep trouble
if I lost that.

500
00:23:05,367 --> 00:23:07,278
(<i>nervous chuckle</i>)

501
00:23:09,287 --> 00:23:11,278
I'll see you all later, eh?

502
00:23:20,447 --> 00:23:22,483
Are you hungry, Frankie?

503
00:23:22,527 --> 00:23:24,836
I'll make you a sandwich.

504
00:23:32,647 --> 00:23:35,639
Jack wanted to talk business
with your father.

505
00:23:35,687 --> 00:23:39,475
He thinks we should get a lawyer
and sue the government.

506
00:23:40,967 --> 00:23:43,765
That is not legal,
what they're doing to us.

507
00:23:46,807 --> 00:23:48,718
Why aren't you saying anything?

508
00:23:54,847 --> 00:23:59,284
You're not going to tell him...
are you?

509
00:23:59,327 --> 00:24:00,965
(<i>quietly</i>):
No.

510
00:24:01,007 --> 00:24:02,235
That's right.

511
00:24:02,287 --> 00:24:04,847
There's nothing to tell.

512
00:24:04,887 --> 00:24:06,479
I'm going out for a few hours

513
00:24:06,527 --> 00:24:09,485
to visit some old friends
from the tennis club and...

514
00:24:09,527 --> 00:24:12,997
when I get home,
we'll all have dinner together.

515
00:24:13,047 --> 00:24:14,924
Right?

516
00:24:14,967 --> 00:24:16,878
But you won't say anything

517
00:24:16,927 --> 00:24:20,158
because it's...
it's just silly, isn't it?

518
00:24:20,207 --> 00:24:22,118
How could we sue anybody?

519
00:24:25,927 --> 00:24:30,205
Oh... do you need
some money, Frankie?

520
00:24:30,247 --> 00:24:33,876
A few dollars to buy
some record albums?

521
00:24:33,927 --> 00:24:36,919
Here, take five dollars.

522
00:24:36,967 --> 00:24:38,878
Or-Or ten.

523
00:24:44,167 --> 00:24:46,044
You promised you were going
to quit.

524
00:24:46,087 --> 00:24:47,998
(<i>slams</i>)

525
00:24:51,407 --> 00:24:53,875
(<i>children laughing</i>)

526
00:24:53,927 --> 00:24:56,316
(<i>dog barking in distance</i>)

527
00:25:04,807 --> 00:25:06,718
Ma, I'm home!

528
00:25:16,327 --> 00:25:18,238
(<i>door opens</i>)

529
00:25:21,007 --> 00:25:22,440
Hey, hey!

530
00:25:22,487 --> 00:25:23,761
You... You stay away from me,
hear me?

531
00:25:23,807 --> 00:25:25,445
You stay away from me...
I don't know who you are

532
00:25:25,487 --> 00:25:26,681
but if you ever
come back here again...

533
00:25:26,727 --> 00:25:28,877
Frankie! Frank, Frank,
calm down, will you?

534
00:25:28,927 --> 00:25:30,042
I'm Dick Kesner.

535
00:25:30,087 --> 00:25:32,157
Now, I want you
to leave your things here

536
00:25:32,207 --> 00:25:34,163
and follow me
into the next room, okay?

537
00:25:34,207 --> 00:25:35,686
They're all waiting for you.

538
00:25:38,647 --> 00:25:40,763
PAULA:
You don't have to be scared.

539
00:25:40,807 --> 00:25:42,684
I'm right here, Frank.
I'll always be here.

540
00:25:42,727 --> 00:25:44,365
But there are laws.

541
00:25:44,407 --> 00:25:46,523
Everything in this country has
to be legal.

542
00:25:46,567 --> 00:25:49,400
So what we need to do is
make some decisions.

543
00:25:49,447 --> 00:25:51,005
That's what Mr. Kesner
is here for.

544
00:25:51,047 --> 00:25:53,277
Many times these decisions
are left up to the courts

545
00:25:53,327 --> 00:25:54,726
but that can be
very expensive, Frank

546
00:25:54,767 --> 00:25:56,325
people fighting
over their children.

547
00:25:56,367 --> 00:25:57,925
Nobody is fighting.

548
00:25:57,967 --> 00:26:00,527
Look at me, Frank.
Nobody is fighting.

549
00:26:00,567 --> 00:26:02,762
(<i>speaking French</i>)

550
00:26:02,807 --> 00:26:05,002
(<i>quietly</i>):
Dad, what's going on?

551
00:26:05,047 --> 00:26:06,480
Dad, what's going on?

552
00:26:06,527 --> 00:26:08,995
(<i>speaking French continues</i>)

553
00:26:09,047 --> 00:26:10,560
Do you remember your grandma,
Eve?

554
00:26:10,607 --> 00:26:12,245
She arrived this morning.

555
00:26:12,287 --> 00:26:13,640
(<i>speaks French</i>)

556
00:26:13,687 --> 00:26:15,120
Hello.

557
00:26:23,127 --> 00:26:26,199
Do you understand what
we're saying to you, Frank?

558
00:26:27,767 --> 00:26:31,555
Your father and I
are getting a divorce.

559
00:26:31,607 --> 00:26:33,996
(<i>speaking French</i>)

560
00:26:34,047 --> 00:26:35,162
Nothing's gonna change.

561
00:26:35,207 --> 00:26:36,845
We're still gonna see
each other.

562
00:26:36,887 --> 00:26:38,718
Stop it, please, Frank.
Don't interrupt.

563
00:26:38,767 --> 00:26:40,962
Frank, you don't
have to read all of this.

564
00:26:41,007 --> 00:26:43,999
Most of it's for your parents...
boring adult business...

565
00:26:44,047 --> 00:26:46,686
but this paragraph right here,
this is important

566
00:26:46,727 --> 00:26:49,287
because it states
who you're gonna live with...

567
00:26:49,327 --> 00:26:51,204
after the divorce...

568
00:26:51,247 --> 00:26:53,078
whose custody you will be in.

569
00:26:53,127 --> 00:26:56,119
And there's a blank space
right here.

570
00:26:56,167 --> 00:26:57,077
(<i>Eve speaking French</i>)

571
00:26:57,127 --> 00:26:58,480
And I want you to go
into the kitchen

572
00:26:58,527 --> 00:27:00,040
sit at the table

573
00:27:00,087 --> 00:27:01,645
and put a name down.

574
00:27:01,687 --> 00:27:02,961
You can take
as long as you want

575
00:27:03,007 --> 00:27:04,565
but when you come back
into this room...

576
00:27:04,607 --> 00:27:07,075
<i>I want to see a name</i>
<i>on that line.</i>

577
00:27:07,127 --> 00:27:10,676
Frank, just write down a name
and this will all be over.

578
00:27:10,727 --> 00:27:12,558
It's gonna be okay.

579
00:27:12,607 --> 00:27:14,279
FRANK:
<i>Dad, what name?</i>

580
00:27:14,327 --> 00:27:15,396
Your mother or your father.

581
00:27:15,447 --> 00:27:17,483
Just put the name there.
It's as simple as that.

582
00:27:17,527 --> 00:27:20,405
And don't look so scared.

583
00:27:20,447 --> 00:27:22,119
It's not a test.

584
00:27:22,167 --> 00:27:24,078
<i>There's no wrong answer.</i>

585
00:27:26,407 --> 00:27:29,285
(<i>man announcing trains</i>
<i>indistinctly</i>)

586
00:27:32,167 --> 00:27:36,365
(<i>melancholy jazz playing</i>)

587
00:27:36,407 --> 00:27:37,317
Hi.

588
00:27:37,367 --> 00:27:38,402
(<i>panting</i>)

589
00:27:38,447 --> 00:27:39,880
One ticket to Grand Central,
please.

590
00:27:39,927 --> 00:27:43,044
That'll be $3.50, sir.

591
00:27:43,087 --> 00:27:45,806
Is it okay
if I write you a check?

592
00:27:50,647 --> 00:27:53,320
Carl, when do I get
to call my father?

593
00:27:53,367 --> 00:27:55,801
You can call him
when we get to New York.

594
00:27:55,847 --> 00:27:57,599
We leave for the airport
in seven hours.

595
00:27:57,647 --> 00:27:58,966
Paris, France 1969

596
00:27:59,007 --> 00:28:01,157
Until then, just sit there.

597
00:28:01,207 --> 00:28:03,801
Be quiet.

598
00:28:03,847 --> 00:28:06,077
You know, Carl,
on the other side of the hotel

599
00:28:06,127 --> 00:28:07,879
they got suites
that face the park.

600
00:28:08,967 --> 00:28:11,959
It's the best room
the FBI can afford.

601
00:28:14,207 --> 00:28:16,198
It's okay, I've stayed in worse.

602
00:28:16,247 --> 00:28:17,521
<i>Mr. Mudrick...</i>

603
00:28:17,567 --> 00:28:18,795
Mr. Mudrick, please.
You have to listen.

604
00:28:18,847 --> 00:28:20,519
I don't want to hear your story.

605
00:28:20,567 --> 00:28:22,239
This is two checks that bounced.

606
00:28:22,287 --> 00:28:23,959
You know how much trouble
I'm in?

607
00:28:24,007 --> 00:28:26,760
No, but listen, I'm telling you,
the bank, they made the mistake.

608
00:28:26,807 --> 00:28:28,240
I'll write you another check
right now!

609
00:28:28,287 --> 00:28:30,118
What, do I look like
I was born yesterday?

610
00:28:30,167 --> 00:28:31,919
Look, it's midnight,
Mr. Mudrick.

611
00:28:31,967 --> 00:28:32,877
Where am I gonna go?

612
00:28:32,927 --> 00:28:34,440
You're a goddamn kid.

613
00:28:34,487 --> 00:28:36,398
Go home.

614
00:28:38,047 --> 00:28:40,277
(<i>baby crying in distance</i>)

615
00:29:22,087 --> 00:29:23,281
I mean, I hope you understand.

616
00:29:23,327 --> 00:29:25,045
My boss sent me to Brooklyn,
then Queens.

617
00:29:25,087 --> 00:29:26,440
Now he wants me in Long Island

618
00:29:26,487 --> 00:29:28,842
to take a few clients out
for a night on the town.

619
00:29:28,887 --> 00:29:32,277
I'm sorry, but we're not allowed
to cash checks from other banks.

620
00:29:32,327 --> 00:29:34,443
How would we know
if they were any good?

621
00:29:34,487 --> 00:29:36,125
What did you say your name was?

622
00:29:36,167 --> 00:29:37,236
Ashley.

623
00:29:37,287 --> 00:29:40,279
Ashley... you know what I found
on the sidewalk out there?

624
00:29:45,527 --> 00:29:47,597
Must've slipped
right off your neck.

625
00:29:51,927 --> 00:29:55,397
Is there something
I can help you with, son?

626
00:29:55,447 --> 00:29:57,722
Well, you see, it's my
grandmother's birthday next week

627
00:29:57,767 --> 00:29:59,678
and I want to get her
something extra-special.

628
00:29:59,727 --> 00:30:01,319
<i>Please, I mean</i>

629
00:30:01,367 --> 00:30:03,676
it's my midterm next week
and my books were stolen.

630
00:30:03,727 --> 00:30:04,762
(<i>raspy coughing</i>)

631
00:30:04,807 --> 00:30:06,604
Please, it's just five dollars.

632
00:30:06,647 --> 00:30:08,205
No one would have to know.

633
00:30:08,247 --> 00:30:10,715
I'm sorry,
but we are not allowed

634
00:30:10,767 --> 00:30:13,964
to take checks
from people we don't know.

635
00:30:22,687 --> 00:30:24,598
(<i>horns honking,</i>
<i>whistle blowing</i>)

636
00:30:46,007 --> 00:30:47,963
(<i>women laughing</i>)

637
00:30:54,007 --> 00:30:55,759
Pleasure to have you back,
Captain Carlson.

638
00:30:55,807 --> 00:30:57,160
What do you think, Angelo?

639
00:30:57,207 --> 00:30:58,720
The tomatoes are ripe
this afternoon.

640
00:30:58,767 --> 00:31:00,678
(<i>women giggling</i>)

641
00:31:06,367 --> 00:31:07,436
Well, what have we here?

642
00:31:07,487 --> 00:31:09,398
- Can I have your autograph?
- You betcha.

643
00:31:09,447 --> 00:31:11,358
- Can I have your autograph, too?
- You gonna be a pilot?

644
00:31:11,407 --> 00:31:13,443
- Mm-hmm!
- All right, then.

645
00:31:13,487 --> 00:31:14,886
There you go.
Work hard in school.

646
00:31:14,927 --> 00:31:16,201
FRANK:
<i>Dear Dad:</i>

647
00:31:16,247 --> 00:31:18,681
<i>I have decided to become</i>
<i>an airline pilot.</i>

648
00:31:18,727 --> 00:31:21,002
<i>I have applied</i>
<i>to all the big airlines</i>

649
00:31:21,047 --> 00:31:23,959
<i>and I have several</i>
<i>promising interviews lined up.</i>

650
00:31:24,007 --> 00:31:25,645
<i>How's Mom?</i>

651
00:31:25,687 --> 00:31:27,564
<i>Have you called her lately?</i>

652
00:31:27,607 --> 00:31:29,598
<i>Love, your son, Frank.</i>

653
00:31:32,807 --> 00:31:34,559
Hello.

654
00:31:34,607 --> 00:31:36,802
I'm Frank Black
from Murrow High School

655
00:31:36,847 --> 00:31:39,315
and I have an appointment
with Mr. Morgan.

656
00:31:39,367 --> 00:31:40,561
You're the young man

657
00:31:40,607 --> 00:31:42,404
who's writing the article
for the school paper.

658
00:31:42,447 --> 00:31:43,880
Yes, ma'am, that's me.
I want to know

659
00:31:43,927 --> 00:31:45,804
everything there is to know
about being a pilot.

660
00:31:45,847 --> 00:31:47,360
What airports
does Pan Am fly to?

661
00:31:47,407 --> 00:31:49,045
What does a pilot make
in a year?

662
00:31:49,087 --> 00:31:51,317
And who tells them
where they're gonna fly to?

663
00:31:51,367 --> 00:31:52,482
Whoa, whoa, whoa. Slow down.

664
00:31:52,527 --> 00:31:53,642
Just take 'em one at a time.

665
00:31:53,687 --> 00:31:54,802
All right. What does it mean

666
00:31:54,847 --> 00:31:56,360
when one pilot says
to another pilot:

667
00:31:56,407 --> 00:31:57,806
"What kind of equipment
are you on?"

668
00:31:57,847 --> 00:32:00,236
They just want to know what kind
of aircraft you're flying:

669
00:32:00,287 --> 00:32:01,606
Is it a DC-8, 707,
Constellation?

670
00:32:01,647 --> 00:32:04,207
And what about those I.D. Badges
that I've seen pilots wear?

671
00:32:04,247 --> 00:32:06,317
Well, every pilot has to have
two things with him

672
00:32:06,367 --> 00:32:08,403
at all times: One is
his airline personnel badge...

673
00:32:08,447 --> 00:32:10,324
looks just like this one here,
from Pan Am...

674
00:32:10,367 --> 00:32:12,881
the other one is
their FAA license...

675
00:32:12,927 --> 00:32:15,157
and that looks just like this.

676
00:32:15,207 --> 00:32:18,756
Oh. Sir, do you think I can
make a copy of this

677
00:32:18,807 --> 00:32:20,525
to put into my article?

678
00:32:20,567 --> 00:32:22,285
Oh, Frank,
you can have that one.

679
00:32:22,327 --> 00:32:23,601
It's three years expired.

680
00:32:23,647 --> 00:32:25,160
Aw, thanks!
And what about your I.D. Badge?

681
00:32:25,207 --> 00:32:26,606
You have an extra one
I could borrow?

682
00:32:26,647 --> 00:32:28,524
Oh, no, I can't help you there.

683
00:32:28,567 --> 00:32:30,398
Those are special-ordered
from Polaroid.

684
00:32:30,447 --> 00:32:31,880
The only way
to get one of those

685
00:32:31,927 --> 00:32:34,395
is to become a real live pilot
for Pan American Airways.

686
00:32:34,967 --> 00:32:37,117
(<i>dialing phone</i>)

687
00:32:37,167 --> 00:32:38,998
(<i>car horns honking,</i>
<i>whistle blowing</i>)

688
00:32:39,047 --> 00:32:40,560
WOMAN (<i>over phone</i>):
Pan Am, may I help you?

689
00:32:40,607 --> 00:32:41,960
FRANK (<i>Southern accent</i>):
Yeah, hello.

690
00:32:42,007 --> 00:32:42,962
I'm calling about a uniform.

691
00:32:43,007 --> 00:32:44,725
WOMAN:
Hold for Purchasing.

692
00:32:44,767 --> 00:32:45,677
FRANK:
Thank you.

693
00:32:45,727 --> 00:32:46,955
WOMAN 2:
Purchasing.

694
00:32:47,007 --> 00:32:48,884
FRANK (<i>Southern accent</i>):
Hi. I'm a copilot

695
00:32:48,927 --> 00:32:50,121
based out of San Francisco.

696
00:32:50,167 --> 00:32:51,964
I flew a flight
into New York last night

697
00:32:52,007 --> 00:32:52,962
but the problem is

698
00:32:53,007 --> 00:32:54,486
I'm headed out to, uh, Paris
in three hours.

699
00:32:54,527 --> 00:32:56,279
WOMAN 2:
How can we help you?

700
00:32:56,327 --> 00:32:57,601
FRANK:
I sent my uniform

701
00:32:57,647 --> 00:32:59,399
to be cleaned through the hotel

702
00:32:59,447 --> 00:33:01,677
and I... I guess
they must have lost it.

703
00:33:01,727 --> 00:33:04,082
WOMAN 2:
<i>They lost a uniform.</i>
<i>Happens all the time.</i>

704
00:33:04,127 --> 00:33:06,038
<i>Go down to the Well-Built</i>
<i>Uniform Company</i>

705
00:33:06,087 --> 00:33:07,122
<i>at Ninth and Broadway.</i>

706
00:33:07,167 --> 00:33:08,520
<i>They're our uniform supplier.</i>

707
00:33:08,567 --> 00:33:10,159
<i>I'll tell Mr. Rosen</i>
<i>you're coming.</i>

708
00:33:10,207 --> 00:33:12,323
ROSEN:
You look too young
to be a pilot.

709
00:33:12,367 --> 00:33:14,005
I'm a copilot.

710
00:33:14,047 --> 00:33:15,605
Why so nervous?

711
00:33:15,647 --> 00:33:17,399
How would you feel if you, uh

712
00:33:17,447 --> 00:33:19,881
lost your uniform
first week on the job?

713
00:33:19,927 --> 00:33:21,406
Relax.

714
00:33:21,447 --> 00:33:23,881
Pan Am's got lots of uniforms.

715
00:33:23,927 --> 00:33:26,077
It's gonna be $164.

716
00:33:26,127 --> 00:33:28,322
Great. I'II, uh,
I'll write you a check.

717
00:33:28,367 --> 00:33:30,358
Sorry, no checks, no cash.

718
00:33:30,407 --> 00:33:32,443
You'll have to fill in
your employee I.D. Number

719
00:33:32,487 --> 00:33:33,522
and then I'll bill Pan Am.

720
00:33:33,567 --> 00:33:35,444
They'll take it out
of your next paycheck.

721
00:33:37,527 --> 00:33:39,119
Even better.

722
00:33:41,047 --> 00:33:42,924
FRANK:
<i>Dear Dad:</i>

723
00:33:42,967 --> 00:33:45,720
<i>You always told me that an</i>
<i>honest man has nothing to fear.</i>

724
00:33:45,767 --> 00:33:47,678
<i>So I'm trying my best</i>
<i>not to be afraid.</i>

725
00:33:47,727 --> 00:33:52,005
<i>I'm sorry I ran away,</i>
<i>but you don't have to worry.</i>

726
00:33:52,047 --> 00:33:54,038
<i>I'm gonna get it all back</i>
<i>now, Daddy.</i>

727
00:33:54,087 --> 00:33:56,362
<i>I promise.</i>
<i>I'm going to get it all back.</i>

728
00:33:56,407 --> 00:33:58,318
(<i>approving murmur</i>)

729
00:34:01,887 --> 00:34:03,798
GIRL:
Are you a real live pilot?

730
00:34:03,847 --> 00:34:05,917
I sure am, little lady.
What's your name?

731
00:34:05,967 --> 00:34:06,877
Celine.

732
00:34:06,927 --> 00:34:08,724
Celine, it's a pleasure
to meet you.

733
00:34:08,767 --> 00:34:10,758
It's a pleasure
to meet you, too.

734
00:34:14,207 --> 00:34:16,880
That's fifty, seventy

735
00:34:16,927 --> 00:34:20,636
eighty, ninety,
one hundred dollars.

736
00:34:20,687 --> 00:34:22,484
You have yourself a great time
in Paris.

737
00:34:22,527 --> 00:34:24,040
I always do.

738
00:34:24,087 --> 00:34:26,920
Excuse me.

739
00:34:26,967 --> 00:34:28,525
I'm John Modiger.
I manage this branch.

740
00:34:28,567 --> 00:34:29,920
I want to thank you
for coming in

741
00:34:29,967 --> 00:34:31,036
and using our institution.

742
00:34:31,087 --> 00:34:32,725
Well, it's a pleasure
to meet you, John.

743
00:34:32,767 --> 00:34:33,677
I'll be back again.

744
00:34:33,727 --> 00:34:34,637
Good.

745
00:34:34,687 --> 00:34:36,439
Have you stayed with us before?

746
00:34:36,487 --> 00:34:39,718
Uh, no, I've been primarily
based on the West Coast.

747
00:34:39,767 --> 00:34:42,964
Is it all right if I write you
a check for the room?

748
00:34:43,007 --> 00:34:43,996
No problem, sir.

749
00:34:44,047 --> 00:34:45,958
Great.

750
00:34:53,007 --> 00:34:54,122
Uh...

751
00:34:54,167 --> 00:34:55,122
I was also wondering

752
00:34:55,167 --> 00:34:56,964
if I could write you
a personal check?

753
00:34:57,007 --> 00:35:00,283
For airline personnel, we cash
personal checks up to $100.

754
00:35:00,327 --> 00:35:02,238
Payroll checks
we cash up to $300.

755
00:35:03,607 --> 00:35:06,246
Did you say $300
for a payroll check?

756
00:35:06,287 --> 00:35:08,676
(<i>typewriter keys clacking</i>)

757
00:35:10,727 --> 00:35:12,957
FRANK:
<i>Dear Dad:</i>

758
00:35:13,007 --> 00:35:15,475
<i>I've decided to become a pilot</i>
<i>for Pan American Airways...</i>

759
00:35:15,527 --> 00:35:18,758
<i>the most trusted name</i>
<i>in the skies.</i>

760
00:35:18,807 --> 00:35:21,367
<i>They've accepted me</i>
<i>into their training program</i>

761
00:35:21,407 --> 00:35:23,284
<i>and told me that if I work hard</i>

762
00:35:23,327 --> 00:35:24,680
<i>I should earn my wings</i>
<i>real soon.</i>

763
00:35:24,727 --> 00:35:27,241
<i>Please get in touch with Joanna</i>
<i>Carlton from the tenth grade.</i>

764
00:35:27,287 --> 00:35:30,518
<i>Tell her I'm sorry that I could</i>
not take her to the Junior Prom.

765
00:35:30,567 --> 00:35:32,478
<i>Love, your son, Frank.</i>

766
00:36:09,767 --> 00:36:10,802
Hello, how are you?

767
00:36:10,847 --> 00:36:11,916
Fine, thank you.

768
00:36:11,967 --> 00:36:13,844
I have a payroll check here
I'd like to cash.

769
00:36:13,887 --> 00:36:15,445
Certainly.

770
00:36:15,487 --> 00:36:16,442
Thank you.

771
00:36:17,967 --> 00:36:19,400
Uh, excuse me.

772
00:36:19,447 --> 00:36:21,244
I'm sure you hear this
all the time

773
00:36:21,287 --> 00:36:23,482
but you have the most
beautiful eyes I have ever seen.

774
00:36:25,167 --> 00:36:26,566
Yeah, I do get that
all the time.

775
00:36:26,607 --> 00:36:28,484
(<i>nervous laugh</i>)

776
00:36:28,527 --> 00:36:30,119
How would you like it?

777
00:36:44,407 --> 00:36:45,681
Oh, I'm sorry, sir.

778
00:36:45,727 --> 00:36:49,436
We won't have any cash until
the banks open in an hour

779
00:36:49,487 --> 00:36:50,636
but, uh, I'm sure

780
00:36:50,687 --> 00:36:53,281
they can cash your check
at the airport.

781
00:36:53,327 --> 00:36:54,726
The airport?

782
00:36:54,767 --> 00:36:57,042
Who cashes checks
at the airport?

783
00:36:57,087 --> 00:36:58,076
Well, the airlines, sir.

784
00:36:58,127 --> 00:37:00,436
They've always taken care
of their own.

785
00:37:00,967 --> 00:37:03,276
(<i>jet passing overhead</i>)

786
00:37:03,327 --> 00:37:05,921
(<i>indistinct flight announcement</i>
<i>over P.A.</i>)

787
00:37:08,647 --> 00:37:09,682
Hello.

788
00:37:09,727 --> 00:37:11,240
Hi. Are you deadheading?

789
00:37:11,287 --> 00:37:12,925
What?

790
00:37:12,967 --> 00:37:14,844
Are you my deadhead to Miami?

791
00:37:14,887 --> 00:37:17,162
Mi...?

792
00:37:17,207 --> 00:37:18,481
Yes, yes.

793
00:37:18,527 --> 00:37:19,596
(<i>laughs</i>)

794
00:37:19,647 --> 00:37:21,922
Yeah, I'm the deadhead.
Here you go.

795
00:37:21,967 --> 00:37:25,357
You're a little late,
but the jump seat is open.

796
00:37:27,007 --> 00:37:27,917
(<i>chuckling</i>):
You know

797
00:37:27,967 --> 00:37:29,480
it's been awhile
since I've done this.

798
00:37:29,527 --> 00:37:30,846
Which one's the jump seat again?

799
00:37:30,887 --> 00:37:33,276
(<i>both laughing</i>)

800
00:37:33,327 --> 00:37:34,840
Have a nice flight.

801
00:37:34,887 --> 00:37:37,037
Are you my deadhead?

802
00:37:39,287 --> 00:37:41,039
STEWARDESS:
Frank, Captain Oliver.

803
00:37:41,087 --> 00:37:42,645
- John Larkin, the copilot.
- Hello.

804
00:37:42,687 --> 00:37:43,756
Fred Tulley, flight engineer.

805
00:37:43,807 --> 00:37:44,876
Frank Taylor, Pan Am.

806
00:37:44,927 --> 00:37:46,679
Thanks for giving me a lift,
boys.

807
00:37:46,727 --> 00:37:48,399
Go ahead and take a seat, Frank.

808
00:37:48,447 --> 00:37:49,516
We're about to push.

809
00:37:49,567 --> 00:37:51,717
What kind of equipment you on,
DC-8?

810
00:37:51,767 --> 00:37:53,359
Uh, 707.

811
00:37:53,407 --> 00:37:55,967
You turning around
on the redeye?

812
00:37:56,007 --> 00:37:58,043
Uh, I'm jumping puddles
for the next few months

813
00:37:58,087 --> 00:37:59,805
trying to earn my keep
running leapfrogs

814
00:37:59,847 --> 00:38:00,962
for the weak and weary.

815
00:38:01,007 --> 00:38:03,919
No shame in that.
We all did it.

816
00:38:10,207 --> 00:38:11,117
Have a seat.

817
00:38:11,167 --> 00:38:12,202
Thank you.

818
00:38:13,167 --> 00:38:15,397
Would you like a drink
after takeoff?

819
00:38:15,447 --> 00:38:17,244
M-Milk?

820
00:38:17,287 --> 00:38:18,402
OLIVER:
80 knots.

821
00:38:18,447 --> 00:38:19,436
LARKIN:
Check.

822
00:38:19,487 --> 00:38:20,840
V-one. Rotate.

823
00:38:20,887 --> 00:38:23,720
(<i>jet engines roaring</i>)

824
00:38:23,767 --> 00:38:25,678
V-two. Positive rate.

825
00:38:25,727 --> 00:38:27,877
Gear up.

826
00:38:27,927 --> 00:38:29,280
FRANK:
<i>Dear Dad:</i>

827
00:38:29,327 --> 00:38:30,680
<i>Today was graduation.</i>

828
00:38:30,727 --> 00:38:32,285
<i>I am now a copilot</i>

829
00:38:32,327 --> 00:38:35,478
<i>earning $1,400 a month</i>
<i>plus benefits</i>

830
00:38:35,527 --> 00:38:37,404
<i>and the best part is</i>

831
00:38:37,447 --> 00:38:39,597
<i>they tell me</i>
<i>my family can fly for free.</i>

832
00:38:39,647 --> 00:38:42,798
<i>So tell Mom to pack her bags</i>
<i>and buy a new swimsuit</i>

833
00:38:42,847 --> 00:38:45,919
<i>because I'm taking us all</i>
<i>to Hawaii for Christmas.</i>

834
00:38:45,967 --> 00:38:47,241
<i>I love you, Dad.</i>

835
00:38:47,287 --> 00:38:49,243
<i>Aloha, Frank.</i>

836
00:38:49,287 --> 00:38:50,800
Hello, deadhead.

837
00:38:50,847 --> 00:38:51,757
Hello.

838
00:38:51,807 --> 00:38:53,399
Enjoying your free ride?

839
00:38:59,047 --> 00:39:01,561
Marci...

840
00:39:01,607 --> 00:39:03,518
did you drop this?

841
00:39:06,287 --> 00:39:07,766
Must've slipped
right off your neck.

842
00:39:07,807 --> 00:39:09,035
No...

843
00:39:09,087 --> 00:39:10,645
(<i>chuckling</i>)

844
00:39:10,687 --> 00:39:12,598
(<i>giggling</i>):
No!

845
00:39:12,647 --> 00:39:14,239
No...

846
00:39:14,287 --> 00:39:16,801
MARCl:
Yes, yes, yes, yes!

847
00:39:16,847 --> 00:39:19,281
(<i>Frank moans passionately</i>)

848
00:39:19,327 --> 00:39:20,396
Yes!

849
00:39:20,447 --> 00:39:22,199
(<i>clanking and clattering</i>)

850
00:39:22,247 --> 00:39:23,282
(<i>Marci panting</i>)

851
00:39:23,327 --> 00:39:27,115
Why are you stopping?

852
00:39:27,167 --> 00:39:30,443
I want to tell you something,
Marci.

853
00:39:30,487 --> 00:39:34,082
This is by far...

854
00:39:34,127 --> 00:39:38,518
the best date I have ever
been on.

855
00:39:38,567 --> 00:39:40,717
(<i>laughing</i>)

856
00:39:57,367 --> 00:39:59,403
WOMAN:
I'd like to open a Money Market,
please.

857
00:39:59,447 --> 00:40:01,358
Okay.

858
00:40:07,247 --> 00:40:10,922
Welcome to Miami Mutual Bank.
How may I help you?

859
00:40:10,967 --> 00:40:14,164
My name is Frank Taylor.
I'm a copilot for Pan Am.

860
00:40:14,207 --> 00:40:16,926
I'd like to cash
this check here, and then

861
00:40:16,967 --> 00:40:19,845
I'd like to take you out
for a steak dinner.

862
00:40:21,167 --> 00:40:22,680
(<i>laughing</i>)

863
00:40:28,247 --> 00:40:29,521
(<i>teller giggling</i>)

864
00:40:29,567 --> 00:40:31,558
And then we feed the checks
into the MICR machine

865
00:40:31,607 --> 00:40:32,835
which uses special ink

866
00:40:32,887 --> 00:40:35,196
to encode the account numbers
on the bottom of the checks.

867
00:40:37,047 --> 00:40:39,436
And where are these numbers?

868
00:40:39,487 --> 00:40:41,637
They're, um... right here.

869
00:40:41,687 --> 00:40:42,915
Right there?

870
00:40:42,967 --> 00:40:44,036
See?

871
00:40:44,087 --> 00:40:46,362
(<i>both giggling</i>)

872
00:40:46,407 --> 00:40:48,363
They're called routing numbers.

873
00:40:48,407 --> 00:40:50,523
So where do the checks
get routed to?

874
00:40:51,487 --> 00:40:53,717
You know, I don't exactly know.

875
00:40:53,767 --> 00:40:55,246
Nobody ever
asked me that before.

876
00:40:55,287 --> 00:40:56,879
(<i>both laughing</i>)

877
00:40:56,927 --> 00:40:58,485
AUCTIONEER:
Our next item up for bid

878
00:40:58,527 --> 00:41:00,722
is also from the Jersey
Central Bank foreclosure.

879
00:41:00,767 --> 00:41:01,882
This is a MICR encoder

880
00:41:01,927 --> 00:41:03,519
a machine used
to encode bank checks.

881
00:41:03,567 --> 00:41:04,761
Do I have an opening bid?

882
00:41:04,807 --> 00:41:06,718
HANRATTY:
<i>Our unknown subject</i>
<i>is a paperhanger</i>

883
00:41:06,767 --> 00:41:08,405
<i>who started working</i>
<i>on the East Coast.</i>

884
00:41:08,447 --> 00:41:10,483
<i>In the last few weeks,</i>
<i>this unsub has developed</i>

885
00:41:10,527 --> 00:41:12,916
<i>a new form of check fraud</i>
<i>which I'm calling "the float."</i>

886
00:41:12,967 --> 00:41:14,002
What he's doing is

887
00:41:14,047 --> 00:41:16,003
he's opening checking accounts
at various banks

888
00:41:16,047 --> 00:41:17,765
then changing the MICR ink
routing numbers

889
00:41:17,807 --> 00:41:19,081
at the bottom of those checks.

890
00:41:19,127 --> 00:41:20,242
Next slide, please.

891
00:41:20,287 --> 00:41:21,436
(<i>projector clanks</i>)

892
00:41:21,487 --> 00:41:23,318
Next slide, please.

893
00:41:23,367 --> 00:41:24,561
Uh, the remote thing is broken.

894
00:41:24,607 --> 00:41:25,722
You'll have to do it by hand.

895
00:41:25,767 --> 00:41:26,756
You've gotta... try the...

896
00:41:26,807 --> 00:41:28,035
FBI Headquarters
Washington, D.C.

897
00:41:28,087 --> 00:41:29,202
Agent Mullen, it should be...

898
00:41:29,247 --> 00:41:31,317
it should be the square button
just there by the side.

899
00:41:31,367 --> 00:41:32,482
This carousel doesn't work.

900
00:41:32,527 --> 00:41:33,880
It's a bad carousel
you got there.

901
00:41:33,927 --> 00:41:34,916
Thank you, Agent Mullen.

902
00:41:34,967 --> 00:41:36,116
Got to move it manually.

903
00:41:36,167 --> 00:41:38,522
This is a map of the 12 banks
of the U.S. Federal Reserve.

904
00:41:38,567 --> 00:41:40,444
Slide.

905
00:41:40,487 --> 00:41:41,522
(<i>clicking</i>)

906
00:41:41,567 --> 00:41:42,966
MICR scanners at every bank

907
00:41:43,007 --> 00:41:45,316
read these numbers
at the bottom of a check...

908
00:41:45,367 --> 00:41:46,516
slide...

909
00:41:46,567 --> 00:41:49,718
and then, ship that check off
to its corresponding branch.

910
00:41:49,767 --> 00:41:52,361
Carl, for those of us who are
unfamiliar with bank fraud

911
00:41:52,407 --> 00:41:54,602
you mind telling us
what the hell

912
00:41:54,647 --> 00:41:56,000
you're talking about?

913
00:41:56,047 --> 00:41:59,801
The East Coast branches are
numbered zero-one to zero-six.

914
00:41:59,847 --> 00:42:01,803
The central branch
is zero-seven, zero-eight

915
00:42:01,847 --> 00:42:02,882
so on, so forth.

916
00:42:02,927 --> 00:42:04,440
You mean those numbers
on the bottom of a check

917
00:42:04,487 --> 00:42:05,522
actually mean something?

918
00:42:05,567 --> 00:42:07,876
All of this was in the report
I filed two days ago.

919
00:42:07,927 --> 00:42:11,886
If you change...
a zero-two to a one-two

920
00:42:11,927 --> 00:42:14,646
that means that check,
which was cashed in New York

921
00:42:14,687 --> 00:42:16,245
does not go
to the New York Federal Branch

922
00:42:16,287 --> 00:42:17,436
but it is rerouted

923
00:42:17,487 --> 00:42:20,604
all the way to the San Francisco
Federal Branch.

924
00:42:20,647 --> 00:42:23,366
The bank doesn't even know the
check has bounced for two weeks

925
00:42:23,407 --> 00:42:25,284
which means our unsub can stay
in one place

926
00:42:25,327 --> 00:42:26,885
paper the same city
over and over again

927
00:42:26,927 --> 00:42:28,406
while his checks circle
the country.

928
00:42:28,447 --> 00:42:31,644
You know,
you want to talk to my wife.

929
00:42:31,687 --> 00:42:34,201
She's the one balances
the checkbook at our house.

930
00:42:34,247 --> 00:42:36,841
(<i>agents laughing</i>)

931
00:42:38,607 --> 00:42:40,962
Next slide.

932
00:42:41,007 --> 00:42:46,400
(<i>three-piece combo</i>
<i>plays soft jazz</i>)

933
00:42:46,447 --> 00:42:47,675
Daddy!

934
00:42:47,727 --> 00:42:48,842
(<i>chuckling</i>)

935
00:42:50,407 --> 00:42:52,284
My son, the birdman.

936
00:42:52,327 --> 00:42:53,282
Some uniform, Frank.

937
00:42:53,327 --> 00:42:55,204
What do you think?

938
00:42:55,247 --> 00:42:56,805
Nice.

939
00:42:56,847 --> 00:42:58,360
Sit down.

940
00:42:58,407 --> 00:42:59,760
(<i>clears throat</i>)

941
00:43:01,287 --> 00:43:03,323
So, Dad... Daddy, have you
gotten the postcards?

942
00:43:03,367 --> 00:43:04,641
Of course.

943
00:43:04,687 --> 00:43:06,837
This fork is ice cold.

944
00:43:06,887 --> 00:43:10,357
No, no, Dad, th-that's
a chilled salad fork.

945
00:43:10,407 --> 00:43:14,844
(<i>whispering</i>):
It's a fancy restaurant,
you know.

946
00:43:14,887 --> 00:43:18,084
(<i>sighing</i>)

947
00:43:18,127 --> 00:43:20,402
Well, here...

948
00:43:20,447 --> 00:43:22,244
l-I got you something.

949
00:43:22,287 --> 00:43:23,925
What's that?

950
00:43:23,967 --> 00:43:25,878
Open it.

951
00:43:29,727 --> 00:43:31,445
You know what those are, right?

952
00:43:31,487 --> 00:43:33,364
Those are the keys

953
00:43:33,407 --> 00:43:36,240
to a 1965 Cadillac
DeVille convertible.

954
00:43:36,287 --> 00:43:38,084
Brand-new, Dad.

955
00:43:38,127 --> 00:43:40,880
Red with white interior

956
00:43:40,927 --> 00:43:44,886
split seats,
air conditioning, the works.

957
00:43:44,927 --> 00:43:46,121
Are you giving me a Cadillac?

958
00:43:46,167 --> 00:43:47,805
Yeah. I'm giving you a Cadillac.

959
00:43:47,847 --> 00:43:49,485
Dad, sh-she's parked downstairs.

960
00:43:49,527 --> 00:43:50,960
When we're done eating lunch

961
00:43:51,007 --> 00:43:53,760
why don't you, you know,
drive on over to Mom's house

962
00:43:53,807 --> 00:43:55,798
pick her up,
take a little joyride?

963
00:43:55,847 --> 00:43:58,805
Do you know what would happen
if the IRS found out

964
00:43:58,847 --> 00:44:02,157
I was driving around
in a new coupe?

965
00:44:02,207 --> 00:44:04,402
I took the train here, Frank.

966
00:44:04,447 --> 00:44:06,483
I'm taking the train home.

967
00:44:08,287 --> 00:44:10,039
All right.

968
00:44:15,047 --> 00:44:17,959
I have plenty of money.

969
00:44:18,007 --> 00:44:20,282
You know, if you
ever, ever need anything...

970
00:44:20,327 --> 00:44:21,555
You worried?

971
00:44:21,607 --> 00:44:23,723
About me?

972
00:44:23,767 --> 00:44:25,564
No, I'm not... I'm not worried.

973
00:44:25,607 --> 00:44:27,643
You think I can't buy
my own car?

974
00:44:27,687 --> 00:44:32,283
Two mice fell
in a bucket of cream, Frank.

975
00:44:32,327 --> 00:44:34,079
Which one am I?

976
00:44:34,127 --> 00:44:36,687
You're that second mouse.

977
00:44:38,407 --> 00:44:41,877
I went by the store today.

978
00:44:41,927 --> 00:44:43,645
I had to close the store
for awhile.

979
00:44:43,687 --> 00:44:45,086
It's all about timing, Frank.

980
00:44:45,127 --> 00:44:46,799
The goddamn government
knows that.

981
00:44:46,847 --> 00:44:48,360
They hit you when you're down.

982
00:44:48,407 --> 00:44:51,160
I wasn't going to let them
take it from me, so I just...

983
00:44:51,207 --> 00:44:54,005
shut the doors myself,
called their bluff.

984
00:44:58,567 --> 00:45:00,603
Sooner or later,
they'll forget about me.

985
00:45:00,647 --> 00:45:02,956
I understand, I...

986
00:45:03,007 --> 00:45:06,044
Have you told Ma?

987
00:45:07,847 --> 00:45:11,999
She's so stubborn, your mother.

988
00:45:14,687 --> 00:45:15,961
Don't worry.

989
00:45:16,007 --> 00:45:18,237
I'm not going to let her go
without a fight.

990
00:45:18,287 --> 00:45:19,402
I been fighting for us...

991
00:45:19,447 --> 00:45:20,846
(<i>gasps quietly</i>)

992
00:45:22,087 --> 00:45:23,520
Dad?

993
00:45:25,767 --> 00:45:28,201
...since the day we... we met.

994
00:45:28,247 --> 00:45:29,999
Daddy, out of all those men

995
00:45:30,047 --> 00:45:33,323
you were the one that
took her home, remember that.

996
00:45:33,367 --> 00:45:36,643
200 men, sitting in
that tiny social hall

997
00:45:36,687 --> 00:45:38,598
watching her dance.

998
00:45:40,967 --> 00:45:43,322
What was the name of that town?

999
00:45:43,367 --> 00:45:44,595
Montrichard, Dad.

1000
00:45:44,647 --> 00:45:46,046
Yeah.

1001
00:45:46,087 --> 00:45:48,840
I didn't speak a word of French

1002
00:45:48,887 --> 00:45:52,084
and six weeks later,
she was my wi...

1003
00:45:52,127 --> 00:45:54,960
She's your wife.

1004
00:45:55,007 --> 00:45:59,046
My son bought me
a Cadillac today.

1005
00:45:59,087 --> 00:46:02,921
I think that calls for a toast.

1006
00:46:02,967 --> 00:46:04,241
(<i>soft jazz playing</i>)

1007
00:46:07,327 --> 00:46:10,205
(<i>inhaling deeply</i>)

1008
00:46:10,247 --> 00:46:13,398
To the best damn pilot
in the sky.

1009
00:46:13,447 --> 00:46:15,039
It's not what you think.

1010
00:46:15,087 --> 00:46:17,601
I'm just a copilot.

