01:07:36,607 --> 01:07:38,563
You got me goin',
got me goin' and goin'...

1518
01:07:38,607 --> 01:07:40,484
(<i>music slows and distorts</i>)

1519
01:07:40,527 --> 01:07:42,040
James, James, please!

1520
01:07:42,087 --> 01:07:43,964
Just stay away from the
hi-fi system, all right?

1521
01:07:44,007 --> 01:07:44,917
It's reel-to-reel.

1522
01:07:44,967 --> 01:07:46,400
You can't wind it like that.

1523
01:07:46,447 --> 01:07:48,324
Don't ever set me free...

1524
01:07:48,367 --> 01:07:49,595
(<i>drink sloshes</i>)

1525
01:07:49,647 --> 01:07:51,717
Christ! Terry!

1526
01:07:51,767 --> 01:07:52,995
This is Italian knit!

1527
01:07:53,047 --> 01:07:53,957
Watch where you're going!

1528
01:07:54,007 --> 01:07:55,360
It's just a shirt, man!

1529
01:07:55,407 --> 01:07:57,875
Frank! Come quick!

1530
01:07:57,927 --> 01:08:01,203
Lance just fell
into the conversation pit!

1531
01:08:05,927 --> 01:08:08,680
Excuse me, you know
where Lance Applebaum is?

1532
01:08:08,727 --> 01:08:10,399
Thank you.

1533
01:08:10,447 --> 01:08:13,041
DOCTOR:
These bottles need to be labeled
when you pick them up.

1534
01:08:13,087 --> 01:08:14,566
Do you understand
how dangerous this is?

1535
01:08:14,607 --> 01:08:16,279
Do you?

1536
01:08:16,327 --> 01:08:18,079
Don't stand there crying,
just nod your head

1537
01:08:18,127 --> 01:08:19,446
and tell me
you won't do it again.

1538
01:08:19,487 --> 01:08:21,284
Now dry up and get back to work.

1539
01:08:21,327 --> 01:08:23,761
WOMAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
Dr. Blair, Dr. Blair

1540
01:08:23,807 --> 01:08:24,922
Dr. Sherwood Blair.

1541
01:08:24,967 --> 01:08:28,596
(<i>gently</i>):
Hey, hey... you okay?

1542
01:08:28,647 --> 01:08:31,081
(<i>sniffling</i>):
He told me to pick up the blood,

1543
01:08:31,127 --> 01:08:33,402
so I did, but he never told me
to label it.

1544
01:08:33,447 --> 01:08:35,324
Hey, it's okay.

1545
01:08:35,367 --> 01:08:37,483
Stop crying.

1546
01:08:37,527 --> 01:08:39,483
What's your name?

1547
01:08:39,527 --> 01:08:42,087
- Brenda.
- Brenda.

1548
01:08:42,127 --> 01:08:44,163
Brenda, I wouldn't worry
about it.

1549
01:08:44,207 --> 01:08:45,640
You know, these doctors

1550
01:08:45,687 --> 01:08:47,917
you know,
they don't know everything.

1551
01:08:47,967 --> 01:08:49,400
It's my first week

1552
01:08:49,447 --> 01:08:52,166
and I think they're
going to fire me.

1553
01:08:52,207 --> 01:08:55,483
No, no, nobody's
going to fire you, Brenda.

1554
01:08:55,527 --> 01:08:57,802
I bet you're good at your job.

1555
01:08:57,847 --> 01:08:59,758
No, I'm not.

1556
01:08:59,807 --> 01:09:03,117
Yeah, I bet if I asked you
to check on the status

1557
01:09:03,167 --> 01:09:05,078
of my friend Lance Applebaum

1558
01:09:05,127 --> 01:09:07,516
that you could do that for me
in a second.

1559
01:09:07,567 --> 01:09:10,445
WOMAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
Nurse Fitzsimmons to Recovery.

1560
01:09:10,487 --> 01:09:12,000
Nurse Fitzsimmons to Recovery.

1561
01:09:12,727 --> 01:09:15,287
Um...

1562
01:09:15,327 --> 01:09:18,160
Mr. Applebaum fractured
his ankle.

1563
01:09:18,207 --> 01:09:21,438
Dr. Ashland is treating him
in exam room seven.

1564
01:09:21,487 --> 01:09:25,036
You see that? No problem.

1565
01:09:26,567 --> 01:09:29,081
This is the emergency chart.

1566
01:09:29,127 --> 01:09:30,526
See that blue star there?

1567
01:09:30,567 --> 01:09:33,240
That means that the patient
has been diagnosed.

1568
01:09:33,287 --> 01:09:35,005
And then,
after he's been treated

1569
01:09:35,047 --> 01:09:38,483
we put a red circle here, see?

1570
01:09:38,527 --> 01:09:40,085
How do you like those braces?

1571
01:09:41,967 --> 01:09:44,037
I guess they're all right.

1572
01:09:44,087 --> 01:09:47,124
I got mine off last year.

1573
01:09:47,167 --> 01:09:49,681
Boy, I hated them.
They were bottoms.

1574
01:09:49,727 --> 01:09:52,878
You know, I still got to wear
my mouth guard.

1575
01:09:52,927 --> 01:09:55,043
You have really nice teeth.

1576
01:09:56,047 --> 01:09:58,083
Well, thank you.

1577
01:09:58,127 --> 01:10:01,324
And you have a pretty smile.

1578
01:10:01,367 --> 01:10:03,119
WOMAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
Custodial to cafeteria.

1579
01:10:03,167 --> 01:10:04,316
(<i>giggles</i>)

1580
01:10:04,367 --> 01:10:05,482
No, I mean it.

1581
01:10:05,527 --> 01:10:07,483
I really think
those braces look good on you.

1582
01:10:07,527 --> 01:10:09,404
Thank you.

1583
01:10:09,447 --> 01:10:11,642
You're welcome.

1584
01:10:14,167 --> 01:10:15,486
Brenda.

1585
01:10:15,527 --> 01:10:16,721
Yeah.

1586
01:10:16,767 --> 01:10:19,645
Do you know if they're hiring
here at the hospital?

1587
01:10:20,967 --> 01:10:22,559
I'm not sure.

1588
01:10:22,607 --> 01:10:24,120
What do you want to do?

1589
01:10:24,167 --> 01:10:27,842
I'm a doctor.

1590
01:10:30,287 --> 01:10:31,879
FRANK:
<i>Dear Dad:</i>

1591
01:10:31,927 --> 01:10:34,157
<i>I've decided to get</i>
<i>off the road for awhile.</i>

1592
01:10:34,207 --> 01:10:36,437
<i>I've taken a night job</i>
<i>at a hospital</i>

1593
01:10:36,487 --> 01:10:38,159
<i>and met</i>
<i>some really nice people.</i>

1594
01:10:38,207 --> 01:10:40,243
<i>Feels good to have my feet</i>
<i>on the ground</i>

1595
01:10:40,287 --> 01:10:43,757
<i>to wake up in the same bed</i>
<i>every night.</i>

1596
01:10:43,807 --> 01:10:47,686
<i>Who knows, maybe I'll even find</i>
<i>someone to settle down with.</i>

1597
01:10:50,207 --> 01:10:52,163
Harvard Medical School...

1598
01:10:52,207 --> 01:10:54,437
top of your class.

1599
01:10:54,487 --> 01:10:57,445
Southern California
Children's Hospital.

1600
01:10:57,487 --> 01:11:01,002
Well, that's a pretty impressive
resume, Dr. Conners

1601
01:11:01,047 --> 01:11:04,119
but unfortunately, uh...
the only thing I need

1602
01:11:04,167 --> 01:11:07,398
is a...
an emergency room supervisor

1603
01:11:07,447 --> 01:11:10,359
for my midnight to 8:00am shift

1604
01:11:10,407 --> 01:11:14,559
someone to baby-sit
six interns and 20 nurses

1605
01:11:14,607 --> 01:11:17,360
but, uh...

1606
01:11:17,407 --> 01:11:21,195
Hell, I doubt that, uh,
you would be interested in that.

1607
01:11:21,247 --> 01:11:23,044
Well, in the past

1608
01:11:23,087 --> 01:11:27,558
they've always let me choose
my own nurses.

1609
01:11:27,607 --> 01:11:30,201
Dr. Connelly?

1610
01:11:30,247 --> 01:11:31,396
Dr. Harris?

1611
01:11:31,447 --> 01:11:32,516
Present.

1612
01:11:32,567 --> 01:11:34,205
Dr. Ashland?

1613
01:11:34,247 --> 01:11:35,805
Dr. Conners...

1614
01:11:35,847 --> 01:11:38,042
You gonna take roll every night?

1615
01:11:38,087 --> 01:11:39,839
Uh, yes, I will, Dr. Ashland

1616
01:11:39,887 --> 01:11:43,641
and if you're going to be late,
I suggest you bring a note.

1617
01:11:43,687 --> 01:11:46,759
(<i>snickering</i>)

1618
01:11:46,807 --> 01:11:48,877
Miss Basmann.

1619
01:11:48,927 --> 01:11:50,599
Miss Mace.

1620
01:11:50,647 --> 01:11:52,160
Miss Strong.

1621
01:11:52,207 --> 01:11:53,560
Here.

1622
01:11:53,607 --> 01:11:55,643
Nurse Brown.

1623
01:11:55,687 --> 01:11:57,678
- Nurse Sanford?
- Here.

1624
01:11:57,727 --> 01:11:59,604
SURGEON (<i>on TV</i>):
30 milligrams of codeine

1625
01:11:59,647 --> 01:12:00,557
every four hours.

1626
01:12:00,607 --> 01:12:02,120
Run the plasma
at 60 drops a minute

1627
01:12:02,167 --> 01:12:04,044
until we calculate
the fluid requirements.

1628
01:12:04,087 --> 01:12:05,964
What do you estimate
the degree and extent

1629
01:12:06,007 --> 01:12:07,076
of the burns, Kildare?

1630
01:12:07,127 --> 01:12:08,685
DR. KILDARE:
Second and third-degree burns

1631
01:12:08,727 --> 01:12:10,365
over about 20 percent
of the body surface.

1632
01:12:10,407 --> 01:12:11,317
Do you concur?

1633
01:12:11,367 --> 01:12:12,277
I concur.

1634
01:12:12,327 --> 01:12:14,204
Let's get him up to Pediatrics.

1635
01:12:14,247 --> 01:12:17,603
WOMAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
Nurse Hopp
to the Nurses' Station South.

1636
01:12:17,647 --> 01:12:20,286
Nurse Hopp
to the Nurses' Station South.

1637
01:12:20,327 --> 01:12:21,680
Hello, Brenda.

1638
01:12:21,727 --> 01:12:22,955
Hi, Dr. Conners.

1639
01:12:23,007 --> 01:12:24,918
You need to sign these.

1640
01:12:24,967 --> 01:12:26,878
Thank you.

1641
01:12:32,447 --> 01:12:34,597
Do you notice anything
different about me, Doctor?

1642
01:12:34,647 --> 01:12:36,080
- You got your braces off!
- Yeah!

1643
01:12:36,127 --> 01:12:37,401
Come here. Let me see.

1644
01:12:37,447 --> 01:12:39,324
I've been trying
to show you all night!

1645
01:12:39,367 --> 01:12:40,516
(<i>thunder rumbling</i>)

1646
01:12:40,567 --> 01:12:42,444
Wow. Good job.

1647
01:12:42,487 --> 01:12:43,966
Yeah?

1648
01:12:44,007 --> 01:12:45,645
So, did it hurt
when they took them off?

1649
01:12:45,687 --> 01:12:46,756
Mine felt so weird after.

1650
01:12:46,807 --> 01:12:48,798
Mm, I keep rubbing my tongue
over them.

1651
01:12:48,847 --> 01:12:50,599
I can't stop.
They're so slippery.

1652
01:12:50,647 --> 01:12:52,046
It feels good, though,
doesn't it?

1653
01:12:52,087 --> 01:12:53,998
Yeah, it feels incredible.

1654
01:12:55,687 --> 01:12:57,723
(<i>thunder rumbles</i>)

1655
01:13:03,287 --> 01:13:04,686
Oh, my.

1656
01:13:04,727 --> 01:13:07,082
I'm... I'm sorry.

1657
01:13:07,127 --> 01:13:09,038
(<i>thunder crashes</i>)

1658
01:13:09,087 --> 01:13:10,998
(<i>passionate moaning</i>)

1659
01:13:18,087 --> 01:13:20,237
WOMAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
Dr. Conners to the ER.

1660
01:13:20,287 --> 01:13:21,845
Dr. Conners to the ER.

1661
01:13:21,887 --> 01:13:23,002
Shouldn't you go?

1662
01:13:23,047 --> 01:13:24,765
No. No, no.

1663
01:13:24,807 --> 01:13:26,718
They have a staff doctor
in the emergency ward.

1664
01:13:26,767 --> 01:13:28,678
We'll be fine.

1665
01:13:32,967 --> 01:13:36,004
(<i>panting</i>):
What if he's in surgery?

1666
01:13:36,047 --> 01:13:39,084
Do you really think
I have to go?

1667
01:13:39,127 --> 01:13:41,641
Oh. In here, Dr. Conners.

1668
01:13:41,687 --> 01:13:43,598
(<i>child sobbing</i>)

1669
01:13:52,727 --> 01:13:55,116
(<i>sobbing</i>)

1670
01:13:57,287 --> 01:14:01,166
Gentlemen, what, uh...
what seems to be the problem?

1671
01:14:01,207 --> 01:14:02,481
Bicycle accident.

1672
01:14:02,527 --> 01:14:06,406
Fractured tibia about
five inches below the patella.

1673
01:14:06,447 --> 01:14:08,358
Hmm.

1674
01:14:10,767 --> 01:14:12,758
- Dr. Harris.
- Yes?

1675
01:14:12,807 --> 01:14:13,796
Do you concur?

1676
01:14:13,847 --> 01:14:17,123
C... Concur with what, sir?

1677
01:14:17,167 --> 01:14:19,044
With what Dr. Ashland just said.

1678
01:14:19,087 --> 01:14:21,601
Do you... Do you concur?

1679
01:14:21,647 --> 01:14:23,842
Uh... well, it was
a bicycle accident.

1680
01:14:23,887 --> 01:14:25,718
Um, the boy told us.

1681
01:14:25,767 --> 01:14:27,246
So you concur?

1682
01:14:27,287 --> 01:14:28,720
Concur? Uh...

1683
01:14:28,767 --> 01:14:30,485
I think we should take an X ray

1684
01:14:30,527 --> 01:14:33,166
then stitch him up
and put him in a walking cast.

1685
01:14:33,207 --> 01:14:34,322
(<i>moans</i>)

1686
01:14:36,327 --> 01:14:38,443
That's very good, Dr. Ashland.
Very good.

1687
01:14:38,487 --> 01:14:41,126
Well, you don't seem
to have much need for me.

1688
01:14:41,167 --> 01:14:42,759
Carry on.

1689
01:14:44,567 --> 01:14:47,206
I blew it, didn't I?

1690
01:14:47,247 --> 01:14:49,317
Why didn't I concur?

1691
01:14:49,367 --> 01:14:52,245
WOMAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
Dr. Henning, call extension 219.

1692
01:14:52,287 --> 01:14:53,766
Dr. Henning, extension 219.

1693
01:14:53,807 --> 01:14:55,718
(<i>vomiting</i>)

1694
01:15:03,847 --> 01:15:07,157
(<i>distant jackhammer drilling</i>)

1695
01:15:10,167 --> 01:15:11,395
FRANK SR:
Make yourself at home!

1696
01:15:11,447 --> 01:15:14,280
Frank Abagnale Sr.

1697
01:15:14,327 --> 01:15:16,682
You're not a cop.

1698
01:15:16,727 --> 01:15:20,356
Special Agent Hanratty, FBI.

1699
01:15:20,407 --> 01:15:21,362
You're not a cop.

1700
01:15:21,407 --> 01:15:23,716
My landlord said
you were not a cop.

1701
01:15:23,767 --> 01:15:25,325
Well, if you're going
to arrest me

1702
01:15:25,367 --> 01:15:26,925
I'd like
to put on a different suit

1703
01:15:26,967 --> 01:15:28,082
if that's okay with you.

1704
01:15:28,127 --> 01:15:29,640
No, no, I'm not here
to arrest you.

1705
01:15:29,687 --> 01:15:31,643
I'm looking for your son.
He's in trouble.

1706
01:15:31,687 --> 01:15:33,040
Do you know where he is?

1707
01:15:35,767 --> 01:15:36,882
If I tell you where he is

1708
01:15:36,927 --> 01:15:38,804
will you promise
not to tell his mother?

1709
01:15:38,847 --> 01:15:40,519
Sure.

1710
01:15:40,567 --> 01:15:43,877
Frank made up a fake I.D.

1711
01:15:43,927 --> 01:15:45,280
And enlisted
in the Marine Corps.

1712
01:15:45,327 --> 01:15:46,680
He's over in Vietnam right now.

1713
01:15:46,727 --> 01:15:48,399
That kid is halfway
around the world

1714
01:15:48,447 --> 01:15:50,915
crawling through the damn jungle

1715
01:15:50,967 --> 01:15:53,242
fighting the Communists, so...

1716
01:15:53,287 --> 01:15:55,403
(<i>shuts refrigerator door</i>)

1717
01:15:55,447 --> 01:15:58,837
Please, don't come to my home
and call my boy a criminal

1718
01:15:58,887 --> 01:16:00,206
because that kid has
more guts...

1719
01:16:00,247 --> 01:16:02,044
I never said he was a criminal,
Mr. Abagnale.

1720
01:16:02,087 --> 01:16:03,725
I said he was in trouble.

1721
01:16:03,767 --> 01:16:06,998
If you'd like to give me a call
and talk, here's my number.

1722
01:16:17,407 --> 01:16:18,886
(<i>pen scribbling</i>)

1723
01:16:18,927 --> 01:16:20,645
You're not a father, are you?

1724
01:16:22,727 --> 01:16:24,957
Pardon me?

1725
01:16:25,007 --> 01:16:26,406
If you were a father,
you'd know.

1726
01:16:26,447 --> 01:16:29,723
I would never give up my son.

1727
01:16:29,767 --> 01:16:33,282
I would never give up my son.

1728
01:16:33,327 --> 01:16:36,558
Yes, sir. I understand.

1729
01:16:36,607 --> 01:16:38,723
Sean, Sean, now get this:

1730
01:16:38,767 --> 01:16:40,120
"Riverbend Apartments

1731
01:16:40,167 --> 01:16:43,477
415 Landover, Atlanta, Georgia."

1732
01:16:43,527 --> 01:16:44,880
Atlanta, Georgia.

1733
01:16:44,927 --> 01:16:46,485
Yeah, I'm on my way
to the airport.

1734
01:16:46,527 --> 01:16:48,483
I'll meet the team in, uh,
in four hours.

1735
01:16:48,527 --> 01:16:49,960
Bye-bye.

1736
01:16:52,127 --> 01:16:53,606
Come on, it's okay.

1737
01:16:53,647 --> 01:16:55,080
(<i>Brenda sobs</i>)

1738
01:16:55,127 --> 01:16:56,924
You don't have to cry.

1739
01:16:56,967 --> 01:16:58,161
I'm sorry.

1740
01:16:58,207 --> 01:16:59,925
I'm so sorry, Frank.

1741
01:16:59,967 --> 01:17:01,366
I can't do this.

1742
01:17:01,407 --> 01:17:03,796
Brenda, listen to me.

1743
01:17:03,847 --> 01:17:06,077
I don't care if you're
a virgin, all right?

1744
01:17:06,127 --> 01:17:07,196
Really, I can wait.

1745
01:17:07,247 --> 01:17:10,284
I'm not a virgin.

1746
01:17:14,047 --> 01:17:16,607
I had an abortion two years ago.

1747
01:17:18,887 --> 01:17:23,085
My parents had a friend do it

1748
01:17:23,127 --> 01:17:27,200
a man that my father
plays golf with.

1749
01:17:27,247 --> 01:17:31,320
And then, when I got better,
they kicked me out of the house.

1750
01:17:31,367 --> 01:17:34,086
I had an abortion and I wasn't
their daughter anymore.

1751
01:17:34,127 --> 01:17:35,560
(<i>gently</i>):
Hey...

1752
01:17:35,607 --> 01:17:36,517
I'm so sorry.

1753
01:17:36,567 --> 01:17:38,046
Please don't be mad at me.

1754
01:17:38,087 --> 01:17:40,123
Please, please,
don't be mad at me.

1755
01:17:40,167 --> 01:17:41,202
No, no.

1756
01:17:41,247 --> 01:17:42,965
Please don't be mad at me.

1757
01:17:43,007 --> 01:17:44,759
Shh. Now... what if...

1758
01:17:44,807 --> 01:17:47,924
what if I spoke
to your parents, right?

1759
01:17:47,967 --> 01:17:49,798
May-Maybe I can
straighten things out, huh?

1760
01:17:49,847 --> 01:17:51,758
Well, I ask them all the time

1761
01:17:51,807 --> 01:17:54,321
but they said I still
can't come home.

1762
01:17:54,367 --> 01:17:58,406
And my daddy's... a lawyer.

1763
01:17:58,447 --> 01:18:00,358
Aw...

1764
01:18:05,407 --> 01:18:08,683
Brenda...

1765
01:18:08,727 --> 01:18:12,037
what if you were engaged
to a doctor?

1766
01:18:12,087 --> 01:18:13,964
Will that change anything?

1767
01:18:14,007 --> 01:18:15,565
What?

1768
01:18:18,727 --> 01:18:22,515
What if I went
to your parents...

1769
01:18:22,567 --> 01:18:24,603
and I spoke to your father...

1770
01:18:27,927 --> 01:18:31,044
and I asked permission
to marry you?

1771
01:18:43,887 --> 01:18:44,797
It's empty.

1772
01:18:44,847 --> 01:18:46,246
Nobody here.

1773
01:19:02,887 --> 01:19:04,764
(<i>classical music playing</i>)

1774
01:19:04,807 --> 01:19:08,277
New Orleans

1775
01:19:08,327 --> 01:19:10,238
(<i>woman laughs</i>)

1776
01:19:10,287 --> 01:19:12,562
Dr. Conners, are you Lutheran?

1777
01:19:12,607 --> 01:19:17,681
Yes, l-I am a Lutheran,
but, please, call me Frank.

1778
01:19:17,727 --> 01:19:20,287
Frank, would you like
to say grace?

1779
01:19:24,887 --> 01:19:28,482
Unless you're not comfortable.

1780
01:19:28,527 --> 01:19:30,438
Absolutely.

1781
01:19:32,127 --> 01:19:34,038
(<i>clears throat</i>)

1782
01:19:39,687 --> 01:19:43,043
Two little mice fell
into a bucket of cream.

1783
01:19:44,647 --> 01:19:46,763
The first mouse quickly
gave up and drowned

1784
01:19:46,807 --> 01:19:48,957
but the second mouse,
he struggled so hard

1785
01:19:49,007 --> 01:19:51,475
that he eventually churned
that cream into butter

1786
01:19:51,527 --> 01:19:53,404
and he walked out.

1787
01:19:53,447 --> 01:19:57,440
- Amen.
- Amen.

1788
01:19:57,487 --> 01:20:00,320
Amen. Oh, that was beautiful.

1789
01:20:00,367 --> 01:20:02,835
The mouse, he churned
that cream into butter.

1790
01:20:02,887 --> 01:20:05,401
(<i>sighing happily</i>)

1791
01:20:05,447 --> 01:20:06,357
That's right.

1792
01:20:06,407 --> 01:20:07,635
That's pretty good.

1793
01:20:07,687 --> 01:20:09,359
Thank you.

1794
01:20:09,407 --> 01:20:11,045
Frank, have you decided
which hospital

1795
01:20:11,087 --> 01:20:12,839
you want to work at
here in New Orleans?

1796
01:20:12,887 --> 01:20:14,957
Well, um, to be quite honest

1797
01:20:15,007 --> 01:20:18,079
I'm thinking
about getting back into law.

1798
01:20:18,127 --> 01:20:19,799
Oh, my!

1799
01:20:19,847 --> 01:20:21,963
Are you a doctor or a lawyer?

1800
01:20:22,007 --> 01:20:26,125
Before I went to medical school,
I passed the bar in California.

1801
01:20:26,167 --> 01:20:27,998
I practiced law for one year

1802
01:20:28,047 --> 01:20:31,244
then I decided why not
try my hand at pediatrics?

1803
01:20:31,287 --> 01:20:33,960
You're just full of surprises.

1804
01:20:34,007 --> 01:20:34,917
Yeah.

1805
01:20:34,967 --> 01:20:37,242
MOTHER (<i>laughing</i>):
Oh, my.

1806
01:20:37,287 --> 01:20:38,242
A doctor and a lawyer.

1807
01:20:38,287 --> 01:20:40,164
Well, I'd say that Brenda
hit the jackpot.

1808
01:20:40,207 --> 01:20:43,040
Where did you go to law school?

1809
01:20:43,087 --> 01:20:44,725
Uh, Berkeley.

1810
01:20:44,767 --> 01:20:45,643
(<i>gasping</i>)

1811
01:20:45,687 --> 01:20:47,006
Berkley, Berkley. Oh, my gosh.

1812
01:20:47,047 --> 01:20:48,526
Isn't that where you went,
Daddy?

1813
01:20:48,567 --> 01:20:50,398
Maybe Frank could come work
for you, Roger.

1814
01:20:50,447 --> 01:20:52,085
You're always saying
how hard it is

1815
01:20:52,127 --> 01:20:53,606
to find
Assistant Prosecutors.

1816
01:20:53,647 --> 01:20:55,717
Could he, Daddy?
Could he, please?

1817
01:20:55,767 --> 01:20:57,200
Could he come work with you,
please?

1818
01:20:57,247 --> 01:20:59,158
Was that snake Hollingsworth
still teaching there

1819
01:20:59,207 --> 01:21:00,401
when you went through Berkley?

1820
01:21:00,447 --> 01:21:02,039
(<i>laughs quietly</i>)

1821
01:21:02,087 --> 01:21:03,520
Hollingsworth.

1822
01:21:03,567 --> 01:21:06,525
Yes. Grumpy old Hollingsworth,
right?

1823
01:21:06,567 --> 01:21:08,080
I tell you. Meaner than ever.

1824
01:21:08,127 --> 01:21:10,038
And that dog of his?

1825
01:21:12,487 --> 01:21:16,560
Tell me, Frank, what was
the name of his little dog?

1826
01:21:24,727 --> 01:21:28,037
I'm sorry. Uh...

1827
01:21:28,087 --> 01:21:29,964
The dog was dead.

1828
01:21:30,007 --> 01:21:31,406
(<i>women cooing</i>)

1829
01:21:31,447 --> 01:21:34,837
How unfortunate.

1830
01:21:34,887 --> 01:21:36,798
Yeah.

1831
01:22:05,847 --> 01:22:08,566
A doctor, a lawyer,
a Lutheran...

1832
01:22:11,167 --> 01:22:14,000
So what are you, Frank?

1833
01:22:14,047 --> 01:22:15,719
'Cause I think you're
about to ask

1834
01:22:15,767 --> 01:22:17,485
for my daughter's hand
in marriage

1835
01:22:17,527 --> 01:22:19,006
and I have a right to know.

1836
01:22:19,047 --> 01:22:21,197
Know what, sir?

1837
01:22:21,247 --> 01:22:23,886
The truth.

1838
01:22:23,927 --> 01:22:28,125
Tell me the truth, Frank.

1839
01:22:28,167 --> 01:22:31,762
What are you doing here?

1840
01:22:31,807 --> 01:22:34,844
What is a man like you doing
with Brenda?

1841
01:22:34,887 --> 01:22:36,878
If you want my blessing

1842
01:22:36,927 --> 01:22:38,963
if you want my daughter

1843
01:22:39,007 --> 01:22:41,885
I'd like to hear it
from you now.

1844
01:22:44,607 --> 01:22:46,518
The truth is, sir, that...

1845
01:22:50,007 --> 01:22:51,486
The truth is that...

1846
01:22:53,687 --> 01:22:56,997
I'm not a doctor,
I'm not a lawyer...

1847
01:22:59,207 --> 01:23:01,801
I'm not an airline pilot.

1848
01:23:01,847 --> 01:23:04,725
I'm... I'm nothing, really.

1849
01:23:10,447 --> 01:23:14,042
I'm-I'm-I'm just a kid who's
in love with your daughter.

1850
01:23:17,167 --> 01:23:19,397
No.

1851
01:23:26,967 --> 01:23:29,197
You know what you are?

1852
01:23:29,247 --> 01:23:31,124
You're a romantic.

1853
01:23:31,167 --> 01:23:34,045
Men like us are nothing
without the women we love.

1854
01:23:34,087 --> 01:23:37,079
I must confess, I'm guilty
of the same foolish whimsy.

1855
01:23:37,127 --> 01:23:39,197
I proposed to Carol
after five dates

1856
01:23:39,247 --> 01:23:42,603
with two nickels in my pockets
and holes in my shoes

1857
01:23:42,647 --> 01:23:44,603
because I knew she was the one.

1858
01:23:44,647 --> 01:23:47,400
So go ahead, Frank.

1859
01:23:50,327 --> 01:23:52,238
Don't be afraid.

1860
01:23:52,287 --> 01:23:55,836
Ask the question you came here
to ask me.

1861
01:23:57,727 --> 01:24:00,116
Sir, uh, uh...

1862
01:24:00,167 --> 01:24:01,646
w-what would I have to do

1863
01:24:01,687 --> 01:24:04,155
to take the bar
here in New Orleans?

1864
01:24:04,207 --> 01:24:06,118
(<i>laughing</i>)

1865
01:24:08,647 --> 01:24:11,957
No, the... the other question.

1866
01:24:12,007 --> 01:24:15,317
(<i>ticking</i>)

1867
01:24:15,367 --> 01:24:19,155
WOMAN:
Right through that door.

1868
01:24:19,207 --> 01:24:21,880
Good luck, Mr. Conners.

1869
01:24:21,927 --> 01:24:23,645
Thank you.

1870
01:24:24,727 --> 01:24:29,198
December 26, 1969

1871
01:24:30,687 --> 01:24:32,245
Hey, Frank...

1872
01:24:32,287 --> 01:24:34,403
you know what I could
never figure out?

1873
01:24:34,447 --> 01:24:37,041
How did you cheat on the
bar exam in Louisiana?

1874
01:24:37,087 --> 01:24:38,805
Why? What's the difference?

1875
01:24:38,847 --> 01:24:41,077
Someone else took the test
for you, didn't they?

1876
01:24:41,127 --> 01:24:43,766
Carl, I'm going to prison
for a long time.

1877
01:24:43,807 --> 01:24:46,446
Seriously,
what's the difference?

1878
01:24:46,487 --> 01:24:48,637
It's a simple question.

1879
01:24:48,687 --> 01:24:50,996
Are you going to eat
that eclair?

1880
01:24:53,447 --> 01:24:56,962
Yeah. I'm saving it for later.

1881
01:24:57,007 --> 01:24:58,725
Well, you want
to split it with me?

1882
01:24:58,767 --> 01:25:02,157
No.

1883
01:25:02,207 --> 01:25:05,517
Give me half that eclair
and I'll tell you.

1884
01:25:14,687 --> 01:25:18,839
I'm going to figure it out
sooner or later.

1885
01:25:25,127 --> 01:25:28,517
You'll be working under
Phillip Rigby in corporate law.

1886
01:25:28,567 --> 01:25:31,445
Why don't you settle in,
organize your desk?

1887
01:25:33,607 --> 01:25:35,006
Thank you.

1888
01:25:35,047 --> 01:25:37,766
We're having lunch at 12:30
with the Attorney General

1889
01:25:37,807 --> 01:25:39,684
and Governor McKeithen.

1890
01:25:39,727 --> 01:25:40,955
Himself.

1891
01:25:41,007 --> 01:25:42,235
The Governor.

1892
01:25:42,287 --> 01:25:43,436
Did we spell it right?

1893
01:25:43,487 --> 01:25:45,000
You sure did.

1894
01:25:45,047 --> 01:25:46,765
Congratulations.

1895
01:25:46,807 --> 01:25:47,922
Thank you, sir.

1896
01:25:47,967 --> 01:25:49,195
Welcome aboard.

1897
01:25:49,247 --> 01:25:51,158
Now...

1898
01:25:55,367 --> 01:25:57,403
Look at this photograph,
Mr. Stewart.

1899
01:25:57,447 --> 01:26:00,484
It's a photograph
of Prentice York

1900
01:26:00,527 --> 01:26:02,483
where they found him, dead.

1901
01:26:02,527 --> 01:26:06,122
Now, here is an enlargement
of part of that photograph.

1902
01:26:06,167 --> 01:26:08,601
This is a photograph
of the defendant's signature

1903
01:26:08,647 --> 01:26:10,046
on a canceled check.

1904
01:26:10,087 --> 01:26:12,476
Now, here is an enlargement
of that same signature

1905
01:26:12,527 --> 01:26:13,642
which matches

1906
01:26:13,687 --> 01:26:16,565
the signature on the letters
that he wrote to Mrs. Simon

1907
01:26:16,607 --> 01:26:18,279
which discuss the possibility

1908
01:26:18,327 --> 01:26:20,522
of defrauding
the great State of Louisiana.

1909
01:26:20,567 --> 01:26:23,718
Your Honor,
ladies and gentlemen of the jury

1910
01:26:23,767 --> 01:26:25,325
this is irrefutable evidence

1911
01:26:25,367 --> 01:26:28,564
that the defendant is,
in fact, lying.

1912
01:26:28,607 --> 01:26:30,199
(<i>echoing thud</i>)

1913
01:26:30,247 --> 01:26:32,044
(<i>chair slams against floor</i>)

1914
01:26:33,047 --> 01:26:38,599
Mr. Conners, this is
a preliminary hearing.

1915
01:26:38,647 --> 01:26:42,037
There is no... defendant.

1916
01:26:42,087 --> 01:26:46,478
There is no... jury.

1917
01:26:46,527 --> 01:26:49,360
It's just me.

1918
01:26:49,407 --> 01:26:50,920
Son...

1919
01:26:50,967 --> 01:26:55,165
what in the hell is wrong
with you?!

1920
01:26:55,207 --> 01:26:57,004
- (<i>applause over TV</i>)
- Is that Mitch?

1921
01:26:57,047 --> 01:26:58,765
Roger! It's Mitch!

1922
01:26:58,807 --> 01:27:00,320
Oh, my,
I lost all track of time.

1923
01:27:00,367 --> 01:27:03,165
MITCH MILLER (<i>on TV</i>):
As studio guests
for the sing-along tonight

1924
01:27:03,207 --> 01:27:05,323
we have the children's choir
of St. Monica's Church

1925
01:27:05,367 --> 01:27:07,119
in New York City.

1926
01:27:07,167 --> 01:27:08,839
Won't you join them and the gang

1927
01:27:08,887 --> 01:27:11,003
in a few songs for the Irish?
Everybody!

1928
01:27:11,047 --> 01:27:13,561
Has anybody here seen Kelly?

1929
01:27:13,607 --> 01:27:16,405
(<i>all but Frank joining in</i>):
K, E, double L, Y

1930
01:27:16,447 --> 01:27:18,802
Has anybody here seen Kelly?

1931
01:27:18,847 --> 01:27:20,838
Have you seen him smile?

1932
01:27:20,887 --> 01:27:23,321
Sure his hair is red,
and his eyes are blue

1933
01:27:23,367 --> 01:27:25,881
And he's Irish
through and through

1934
01:27:25,927 --> 01:27:28,282
Has anybody here seen Kelly

1935
01:27:28,327 --> 01:27:30,682
Kelly from the Emerald Isle?

1936
01:27:30,727 --> 01:27:33,287
Has anybody here seen Kelly?

1937
01:27:33,327 --> 01:27:35,397
K, E, double L, Y

1938
01:27:35,447 --> 01:27:38,086
(<i>joining in</i>):
Has anybody here seen Kelly?

1939
01:27:38,127 --> 01:27:40,197
Have you seen him smile?

1940
01:27:40,247 --> 01:27:42,841
Sure his hair is red,
and his eyes are blue

1941
01:27:42,887 --> 01:27:45,196
And he's Irish
through and through

1942
01:27:45,247 --> 01:27:47,477
Has anybody here
seen Kelly...

1943
01:27:47,527 --> 01:27:49,757
JUDY GARLAND (<i>on record</i>):
Embrace me

1944
01:27:49,807 --> 01:27:55,040
My sweet embraceable you

1945
01:27:55,087 --> 01:27:58,124
Embrace me

1946
01:27:58,167 --> 01:28:04,276
You irreplaceable you

1947
01:28:04,327 --> 01:28:07,239
Just one look at you

1948
01:28:07,287 --> 01:28:13,044
My heart grew tipsy in me

1949
01:28:13,087 --> 01:28:15,806
You and you alone

1950
01:28:15,847 --> 01:28:22,116
Bring out the gypsy in me

1951
01:28:22,367 --> 01:28:25,006
I love all

1952
01:28:25,047 --> 01:28:31,316
The many charms about you

1953
01:28:31,367 --> 01:28:34,120
Above all

1954
01:28:34,167 --> 01:28:37,045
I want my arms about you...

1955
01:28:37,087 --> 01:28:38,759
(<i>whispers</i>):
Dad.

1956
01:28:40,167 --> 01:28:43,284
...Don't be
a naughty baby...

1957
01:28:43,327 --> 01:28:45,283
What are you doing here?

1958
01:28:45,327 --> 01:28:49,479
I... l-I came to see you.

1959
01:28:49,527 --> 01:28:52,439
...My sweet embraceable...

1960
01:28:52,487 --> 01:28:54,557
What are you doing
dressed like this?

1961
01:28:54,607 --> 01:28:56,438
I took a job. A government job.

1962
01:28:56,487 --> 01:28:57,806
You see what I'm doing?

1963
01:28:57,847 --> 01:28:59,485
Do you have a good lawyer?

1964
01:28:59,527 --> 01:29:01,916
Well... I sort of
am a lawyer now.

1965
01:29:01,967 --> 01:29:05,596
Look at this letter.
The IRS wants more.

1966
01:29:05,647 --> 01:29:08,002
I had a deal with them:
Two penalties.

1967
01:29:08,047 --> 01:29:11,278
They ate the cake,
now they want the crumbs.

1968
01:29:11,327 --> 01:29:14,046
I want to sue them.

1969
01:29:14,087 --> 01:29:16,885
Now they want the crumbs.

1970
01:29:16,927 --> 01:29:18,918
They... Here, sit down.

1971
01:29:18,967 --> 01:29:21,481
They're trying to scare me,
intimidate me.

1972
01:29:21,527 --> 01:29:23,961
You know what?

1973
01:29:24,007 --> 01:29:27,283
You know what?
I'll make them chase me...

1974
01:29:27,327 --> 01:29:29,636
for the rest of their lives.

1975
01:29:35,447 --> 01:29:38,962
Hey, it's great
to see you, Daddy.

1976
01:29:39,007 --> 01:29:43,239
Listen, sit down, I...
I want to show you something.

1977
01:29:44,927 --> 01:29:47,157
I came here to give you this.

1978
01:29:47,207 --> 01:29:51,280
It's an invitation
to an engagement party.

1979
01:29:52,327 --> 01:29:55,046
Daddy, I'm getting married.

1980
01:29:55,087 --> 01:29:57,885
Can you believe that?
I'm getting married.

1981
01:29:57,927 --> 01:30:00,361
You don't need to worry
about anything now, Dad.

1982
01:30:00,407 --> 01:30:02,523
Listen, I'm getting
a brand-new Cadillac.

1983
01:30:02,567 --> 01:30:04,285
I'm getting a $60,000 house.

1984
01:30:04,327 --> 01:30:06,204
I'm-I'm getting it all back.

1985
01:30:06,247 --> 01:30:08,636
All-All the jewelry,
all the furs, everything, Dad.

1986
01:30:08,687 --> 01:30:11,281
Everything they took from us,
I'm going to get it back.

1987
01:30:11,327 --> 01:30:13,079
Now...

1988
01:30:13,127 --> 01:30:16,676
has Ma seen you
dressed like this?

1989
01:30:16,727 --> 01:30:20,083
Yeah, she came
to pick up some boxes.

1990
01:30:20,127 --> 01:30:21,685
That's okay, that's okay,
you know why?

1991
01:30:21,727 --> 01:30:23,683
'Cause she... she's going
to the wedding with us.

1992
01:30:23,727 --> 01:30:25,479
I'm going to get you
a brand-new suit, Dad.

1993
01:30:25,527 --> 01:30:26,846
I'm getting you
a brand-new suit.

1994
01:30:26,887 --> 01:30:29,401
One of those Manhattan Eagle,
three-button, black pearl suits.

1995
01:30:29,447 --> 01:30:30,436
You'll look great.

1996
01:30:30,487 --> 01:30:31,840
Those are nice. Yeah.

1997
01:30:31,887 --> 01:30:34,401
She won't see me.

1998
01:30:35,367 --> 01:30:37,164
Well, have you tried
to call her?

1999
01:30:37,207 --> 01:30:39,243
Uh-uh.

2000
01:30:39,287 --> 01:30:41,676
Why don't... why don't you
call her right now?

2001
01:30:41,727 --> 01:30:44,116
Dad, why don't you
call her right now? Here.

2002
01:30:44,167 --> 01:30:46,237
Dad, just call her.
Call her for me.

2003
01:30:46,287 --> 01:30:47,925
You call her, and you tell her

2004
01:30:47,967 --> 01:30:50,561
I have two first-class tickets
to go see her son's wedding...

2005
01:30:50,607 --> 01:30:53,075
Your mother's married now,
to my friend Jack Barnes.

2006
01:30:53,127 --> 01:30:56,358
They have a house
in Long Island.

2007
01:30:56,407 --> 01:30:59,956
(<i>whispering</i>):
I had an FBI agent come see me.

2008
01:31:00,007 --> 01:31:01,759
You got their number, son.

2009
01:31:01,807 --> 01:31:03,798
The guy looked scared.

2010
01:31:03,847 --> 01:31:08,159
The United States government,
champ, running for the hills.

2011
01:31:08,207 --> 01:31:10,357
Pow! To the moon!

2012
01:31:21,087 --> 01:31:23,885
Dad... it's over.

2013
01:31:25,287 --> 01:31:27,164
I'm going to stop now.

2014
01:31:27,207 --> 01:31:29,198
But y-you've...

2015
01:31:29,247 --> 01:31:31,283
They're never going
to catch you, Frank.

2016
01:31:31,327 --> 01:31:33,443
- Dad, she wouldn't do that.
- Why won't you sit down?

2017
01:31:33,487 --> 01:31:35,318
- Why would she do that to you?
- Come on, sit.

2018
01:31:35,367 --> 01:31:36,959
Come on, sit with me.
Have a drink.

2019
01:31:37,007 --> 01:31:38,235
I'm your father.

2020
01:31:38,287 --> 01:31:41,563
Then ask me to stop.

2021
01:31:41,607 --> 01:31:43,723
(<i>quietly</i>):
Then ask me to stop.

2022
01:31:46,527 --> 01:31:48,438
You can't stop.

2023
01:31:50,447 --> 01:31:52,199
Where are you going?

2024
01:31:52,247 --> 01:31:54,522
Come on, Frank,
where are you going?

2025
01:31:54,567 --> 01:31:55,920
Where are you going?

2026
01:31:55,967 --> 01:31:57,844
Where are you going tonight?

2027
01:31:57,887 --> 01:31:59,002
Someplace exotic?

2028
01:31:59,047 --> 01:32:00,275
Where are you going tonight?

2029
01:32:00,327 --> 01:32:01,442
Tahiti, Hawaii?

2030
01:32:11,047 --> 01:32:14,881
(<i>phone ringing</i>)

2031
01:32:18,527 --> 01:32:21,325
This is Hanratty.

2032
01:32:21,367 --> 01:32:23,278
FRANK:
Hello, Carl.

2033
01:32:23,327 --> 01:32:25,204
Merry Christmas.

2034
01:32:25,247 --> 01:32:27,522
How are you, Dr. Conners?

2035
01:32:27,567 --> 01:32:31,845
Carl, I haven't been Dr. Conners
for months now.

2036
01:32:31,887 --> 01:32:33,605
(<i>Hanratty sniffles,</i>
<i>clears throat</i>)

2037
01:32:33,647 --> 01:32:38,277
Well... I'm sitting here
in my office on Christmas Eve.

2038
01:32:38,327 --> 01:32:39,840
What do you want?

2039
01:32:39,887 --> 01:32:44,005
(<i>instrumental version "I'll Be</i>
<i>Home for Christmas" playing</i>)

2040
01:32:44,047 --> 01:32:46,686
(<i>sighs</i>):
Okay.

2041
01:32:50,847 --> 01:32:52,963
I want it to be over.

2042
01:32:56,047 --> 01:32:58,277
Uh... I want it to be over.

2043
01:32:58,327 --> 01:33:00,124
I'm getting married.

2044
01:33:00,167 --> 01:33:02,078
You know, I'm settling down.

2045
01:33:02,127 --> 01:33:04,004
You've stolen almost $4 million.

2046
01:33:04,047 --> 01:33:06,242
You think we can just
call that a wedding present?

2047
01:33:06,287 --> 01:33:09,165
Nah, this isn't something you
get to walk away from, Frank.

2048
01:33:09,207 --> 01:33:10,640
I want to call a truce.

2049
01:33:10,687 --> 01:33:11,756
No truce.

2050
01:33:11,807 --> 01:33:13,638
You will be caught,
you will go to prison.

2051
01:33:13,687 --> 01:33:15,200
Where did you think
this was going?

2052
01:33:15,247 --> 01:33:18,478
Please leave me alone, Carl.

2053
01:33:18,527 --> 01:33:19,801
Please?

2054
01:33:19,847 --> 01:33:21,599
I'm getting close, aren't I?

2055
01:33:21,647 --> 01:33:23,683
You're scared because
I'm getting close.

2056
01:33:23,727 --> 01:33:26,764
I know you... you rented
that car in Shreveport

2057
01:33:26,807 --> 01:33:29,640
and you stayed in that hotel
on Lake Charles.

2058
01:33:29,687 --> 01:33:31,598
You want to run, be my guest.

2059
01:33:31,647 --> 01:33:33,877
Your checks don't lie
as well as you do.

2060
01:33:33,927 --> 01:33:36,805
Stop chasing me.

2061
01:33:38,927 --> 01:33:41,487
I can't stop.

2062
01:33:41,527 --> 01:33:43,916
It's my job.

2063
01:33:43,967 --> 01:33:46,356
It's okay, Carl.

2064
01:33:46,407 --> 01:33:49,683
I just thought I'd ask,
you know?

2065
01:33:52,007 --> 01:33:55,920
Hey. Merry Christmas, huh?

2066
01:33:55,967 --> 01:33:59,039
(<i>click and dial tone</i>)

2067
01:33:59,087 --> 01:34:01,396
I love my job.

2068
01:34:01,447 --> 01:34:03,005
All right... (<i>clears throat</i>)

2069
01:34:03,047 --> 01:34:04,446
Let's get every newspaper
we can

2070
01:34:04,487 --> 01:34:06,921
every newspaper in Louisiana
for the last two months.

2071
01:34:06,967 --> 01:34:08,161
What are we looking for?

2072
01:34:08,207 --> 01:34:10,437
Engagement announcements,
name of Conners.

2073
01:34:10,487 --> 01:34:12,717
Conners?! Come on, Carl,
the kid would've

2074
01:34:12,767 --> 01:34:14,200
changed his name by now.

2075
01:34:14,247 --> 01:34:16,886
Mm-mm. He can't change it.

2076
01:34:16,927 --> 01:34:18,724
She thinks he's Conners.

2077
01:34:18,767 --> 01:34:20,883
If he loses the name,
he loses the girl.

2078
01:34:20,927 --> 01:34:22,440
I can't give you anything

2079
01:34:22,927 --> 01:34:26,124
But love, baby

2080
01:34:26,167 --> 01:34:29,842
That's the only thing
I have plenty of

2081
01:34:29,887 --> 01:34:30,922
Baby

2082
01:34:30,967 --> 01:34:32,559
Dreamin' a while,
schemin' a while...

2083
01:34:32,607 --> 01:34:34,165
- Congratulations.
- You having a good time?

2084
01:34:34,207 --> 01:34:37,438
...You're sure to find

2085
01:34:37,487 --> 01:34:39,921
- Happiness, and I guess
- Keep dancing, huh?

2086
01:34:39,967 --> 01:34:41,878
All those things
you've always pined for...

2087
01:34:41,927 --> 01:34:43,804
- Oh.
- Hi.

2088
01:34:43,847 --> 01:34:44,802
Oh, me too. Thank you.

2089
01:34:44,847 --> 01:34:46,599
I'm going to, uh,
the little boys' room.

2090
01:34:46,647 --> 01:34:47,762
- Okay.
- Okay.

2091
01:34:47,807 --> 01:34:49,240
Hurry back.

2092
01:34:54,847 --> 01:34:57,884
(<i>car approaching</i>)

2093
01:34:57,927 --> 01:35:00,839
(<i>brakes squeaking</i>)

2094
01:35:03,207 --> 01:35:04,322
Good evening.

2095
01:35:04,367 --> 01:35:05,846
I'm Agent Hanratty
with the FBI.

2096
01:35:05,887 --> 01:35:08,162
We'd like to have
a few quiet words

2097
01:35:08,207 --> 01:35:09,435
with your host, if possible.

2098
01:35:09,487 --> 01:35:11,398
MAN:
I'll get him.

2099
01:35:12,527 --> 01:35:13,880
Right over there, sir.

2100
01:35:13,927 --> 01:35:16,361
- Hi, Roger. How are you?
- Hi, Vin.

2101
01:35:16,407 --> 01:35:18,637
Good evening, gentlemen.
I'm Roger Strong.

2102
01:35:18,687 --> 01:35:20,120
Carl Hanratty, FBI.

2103
01:35:20,167 --> 01:35:22,237
This is Agents Amdursky and Fox.

2104
01:35:22,287 --> 01:35:24,323
Sorry to crash your party, sir.

2105
01:35:24,367 --> 01:35:26,198
Not at all.
What can I do for you?

2106
01:35:26,247 --> 01:35:29,478
If it's not too much trouble,
I'd like to meet the groom.

2107
01:35:29,527 --> 01:35:32,360
Is there a problem?

2108
01:35:32,407 --> 01:35:34,079
- (<i>laughter</i>)
- Frank! Frank!

2109
01:35:34,127 --> 01:35:35,162
Can you hold all these?

2110
01:35:35,207 --> 01:35:36,720
(<i>whispering</i>):
Yeah. Come here.

2111
01:35:36,767 --> 01:35:38,962
They're checks.
They're from my dad's friends.

2112
01:35:39,007 --> 01:35:41,157
They're for us, so we can
start a new life... Hey!

2113
01:35:41,207 --> 01:35:42,720
What are you doing?
What's wrong?

2114
01:35:42,767 --> 01:35:44,405
We have to leave.

2115
01:35:44,447 --> 01:35:46,165
What?!

2116
01:35:46,207 --> 01:35:48,084
Brenda, you love me, right?

2117
01:35:48,127 --> 01:35:49,526
Yes.

2118
01:35:49,567 --> 01:35:51,125
I mean, you'd love me
no matter what.

2119
01:35:51,167 --> 01:35:52,077
Yes.

2120
01:35:52,127 --> 01:35:53,037
I mean, you'd love me

2121
01:35:53,087 --> 01:35:54,566
whether I was sick
or whether I was poor

2122
01:35:54,607 --> 01:35:55,881
or even if I had
a different name.

2123
01:35:55,927 --> 01:35:57,326
Frank, where'd you get
all that money?

2124
01:35:57,367 --> 01:35:58,561
Brenda, listen. A name, right?

2125
01:35:58,607 --> 01:35:59,801
A name, it doesn't matter.

2126
01:35:59,847 --> 01:36:01,360
My name is Frank Conners, right?

2127
01:36:01,407 --> 01:36:02,601
- That's who I am with you.
- Yes.

2128
01:36:02,647 --> 01:36:03,841
But-but we all have secrets.

2129
01:36:03,887 --> 01:36:05,240
You know,
sometimes when I travel

2130
01:36:05,287 --> 01:36:07,482
I use the name Frank Taylor.
That-That's my secret.

2131
01:36:07,527 --> 01:36:09,404
- Frank Taylor?!
- Yeah, Frank Taylor, you know?

2132
01:36:09,447 --> 01:36:10,596
- Frank Black.
- Frank Black?!

2133
01:36:10,647 --> 01:36:11,716
Yeah, it doesn't matter.

2134
01:36:11,767 --> 01:36:14,361
Why are you saying all this?

2135
01:36:14,407 --> 01:36:17,001
Brenda... Brenda, I don't want
to lie to you anymore.

2136
01:36:17,047 --> 01:36:18,446
All right? I'm not a doctor.

2137
01:36:18,487 --> 01:36:20,159
I never went to medical school.

2138
01:36:20,207 --> 01:36:22,801
I'm not a lawyer or a Harvard
graduate or a Lutheran.

2139
01:36:22,847 --> 01:36:25,281
Brenda, I ran away from home
a year and a half ago

2140
01:36:25,327 --> 01:36:27,079
when I was 16.

2141
01:36:27,127 --> 01:36:29,766
Frank...

2142
01:36:29,807 --> 01:36:31,957
Frank?

2143
01:36:32,007 --> 01:36:33,884
You're not a Lutheran?

2144
01:36:33,927 --> 01:36:36,282
Brenda... you see
all this money?

2145
01:36:36,327 --> 01:36:38,238
You see all this money?
I have more.

2146
01:36:38,287 --> 01:36:40,755
I have plenty more.

2147
01:36:40,807 --> 01:36:41,762
I have enough money

2148
01:36:41,807 --> 01:36:43,604
to last us
for the rest of our lives

2149
01:36:43,647 --> 01:36:45,046
- (<i>gasps</i>)
- Look.

2150
01:36:45,087 --> 01:36:47,601
Frank, stop teasing me.

2151
01:36:47,647 --> 01:36:48,875
You're Frank Conners.

2152
01:36:48,927 --> 01:36:51,839
You're Frank Conners,
and you're 28 years old and...

2153
01:36:51,887 --> 01:36:53,115
(<i>whispering</i>):
Brenda...

2154
01:36:53,167 --> 01:36:55,078
Why would you lie to me?

2155
01:36:55,127 --> 01:36:57,243
- Brenda, Brenda...
- I want to know your name.

2156
01:36:57,287 --> 01:36:59,278
- Listen to me, Brenda.
- Tell me your name.

2157
01:36:59,327 --> 01:37:00,601
We can live anywhere we want

2158
01:37:00,647 --> 01:37:02,160
but you have to trust me,
Brenda.

2159
01:37:02,207 --> 01:37:03,435
- Do you trust me?
- Yes.

2160
01:37:03,487 --> 01:37:05,443
- Do you love me, Brenda?
- Yes.

2161
01:37:05,487 --> 01:37:06,806
- You love me?
- I love you.

2162
01:37:06,847 --> 01:37:09,281
Excuse me, Mother.

2163
01:37:09,327 --> 01:37:11,602
Honey, this is Mr. Hanratty.
My wife Carol.

2164
01:37:11,647 --> 01:37:13,126
- Oh, Mister...?
- Hanratty, ma'am.

2165
01:37:13,167 --> 01:37:14,282
- Ratty.
- Yes.

2166
01:37:14,327 --> 01:37:15,999
Have you seen Frank or Brenda?

2167
01:37:16,047 --> 01:37:18,038
L-I think they went upstairs.

2168
01:37:23,367 --> 01:37:24,925
Frank...

2169
01:37:26,567 --> 01:37:28,398
(<i>whispers</i>):
Brenda, come here.

2170
01:37:28,447 --> 01:37:30,403
Okay, in two days,
you're going to meet me

2171
01:37:30,447 --> 01:37:32,438
at Miami International
Airport, all right?

2172
01:37:32,487 --> 01:37:34,955
You're going to leave the house
after your parents go to sleep.

2173
01:37:35,007 --> 01:37:36,122
You're going to take a taxicab.

2174
01:37:36,167 --> 01:37:37,839
You give the taxi driver
this money right here

2175
01:37:37,887 --> 01:37:39,639
and you tell him to drive
all through the night.

2176
01:37:39,687 --> 01:37:41,439
Brenda, you're going
to leave at 10:00am.

2177
01:37:41,487 --> 01:37:43,205
- 10:00am, all right?
- But...

2178
01:37:43,247 --> 01:37:45,442
(<i>scatting</i>)

2179
01:37:45,487 --> 01:37:47,603
I never stop

2180
01:37:47,647 --> 01:37:50,639
Till I get to the top...

2181
01:37:50,687 --> 01:37:53,804
(<i>jazz continues in distance</i>)

2182
01:38:01,487 --> 01:38:02,966
Which room, sir?

2183
01:38:03,007 --> 01:38:04,281
In the corner.

2184
01:38:04,327 --> 01:38:05,555
You have to listen to me,
all right?

2185
01:38:05,607 --> 01:38:07,518
The International Terminal
in Miami, all right? Say it.

2186
01:38:07,567 --> 01:38:09,000
Okay, the International
Terminal in Miami.

2187
01:38:09,047 --> 01:38:10,366
- No matter what...
- No matter what...

2188
01:38:10,407 --> 01:38:12,284
- You're going to take a taxicab.
- I will take a taxi.

2189
01:38:12,327 --> 01:38:13,806
You're going to be there
at 10:00am.

2190
01:38:13,847 --> 01:38:15,041
I will be there at 10:00am,
no matter what.

2191
01:38:15,087 --> 01:38:15,997
- In two days.
- Two days.

2192
01:38:16,047 --> 01:38:16,957
Two days, Brenda. Two days.

2193
01:38:17,007 --> 01:38:18,440
In two days, I'll be there

2194
01:38:18,487 --> 01:38:20,045
no matter what, at 10:00am.

2195
01:38:26,607 --> 01:38:28,040
You're not going
to tell anyone, Brenda.

2196
01:38:28,087 --> 01:38:29,156
You have to promise me, now.

2197
01:38:29,207 --> 01:38:30,526
(<i>crying</i>):
Frank, please!

2198
01:38:30,567 --> 01:38:32,762
Before you go,
please tell me your name.

2199
01:38:32,807 --> 01:38:35,037
Please, tell me.

2200
01:38:35,087 --> 01:38:39,524
Frank William Abagnale Jr.

2201
01:38:41,407 --> 01:38:43,682
(<i>ominous music playing</i>)

2202
01:38:47,367 --> 01:38:49,517
(<i>light, childlike theme plays</i>)

2203
01:38:52,327 --> 01:38:53,919
(<i>wind blowing</i>)

2204
01:38:56,007 --> 01:39:00,683
(<i>ominous theme building</i>)

2205
01:39:00,727 --> 01:39:03,195
(<i>childlike theme returns</i>)

2206
01:39:05,447 --> 01:39:08,325
(<i>shuddering</i>)

2207
01:39:24,607 --> 01:39:26,598
WOMAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
National Airlines

2208
01:39:26,647 --> 01:39:29,286
flight number 27, serving
Fort Myers, Sarasota, Tampa

2209
01:39:29,327 --> 01:39:32,797
and New York Kennedy,
is now available at gate n...

2210
01:39:34,727 --> 01:39:38,879
Skycap, Gate 14.
Skycap, Gate 14.

2211
01:39:38,927 --> 01:39:40,246
Taxi!

2212
01:39:40,287 --> 01:39:43,165
(<i>announcements continue</i>
<i>indistinctly over P.A.</i>)

2213
01:39:50,247 --> 01:39:52,397
MAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
Your attention...

2214
01:40:42,687 --> 01:40:45,520
(<i>sighing</i>)

2215
01:40:45,567 --> 01:40:48,320
Brenda.

2216
01:40:57,607 --> 01:40:59,484
AMDURSKY:
<i>This guy's a no-show.</i>

2217
01:40:59,527 --> 01:41:00,846
<i>He must've got wise to us.</i>

2218
01:41:00,887 --> 01:41:02,366
HANRATTY:
<i>Maybe he was tipped.</i>

2219
01:41:02,407 --> 01:41:04,045
If he's not here today,
he'll be tomorrow.

2220
01:41:04,087 --> 01:41:05,805
We'll get him before
he leaves the country.

2221
01:41:05,847 --> 01:41:07,166
He doesn't have a passport.

2222
01:41:07,207 --> 01:41:09,516
For the last six months, he's
gone to Harvard and Berkeley.

2223
01:41:09,567 --> 01:41:10,920
I'm betting he can get
a passport.

2224
01:41:10,967 --> 01:41:12,685
So we have all our men
waiting for him here

2225
01:41:12,727 --> 01:41:13,637
in Miami International.

2226
01:41:13,687 --> 01:41:15,325
He's used it before.
He knows the layout.

2227
01:41:15,367 --> 01:41:17,164
I talked to Miami police;
they've offered us

2228
01:41:17,207 --> 01:41:18,799
50 uniformed cops
in two shifts of 25.

2229
01:41:18,847 --> 01:41:20,883
With our guys, that's almost
100 men in one airport.

2230
01:41:20,927 --> 01:41:22,645
Don't you think
we should spread it around?

2231
01:41:22,687 --> 01:41:24,245
No, no, this is the exit point.

2232
01:41:24,287 --> 01:41:26,403
Well, how do you know
he hasn't rented a car

2233
01:41:26,447 --> 01:41:28,563
and driven to airports
in New York, Atlanta?

2234
01:41:28,607 --> 01:41:30,040
Because I'm not in New York.

2235
01:41:30,087 --> 01:41:31,281
I'm not in Atlanta.

2236
01:41:31,327 --> 01:41:33,124
Yes, this is, uh, Frank Roberts

2237
01:41:33,167 --> 01:41:35,123
and I'm letting
all the universities

2238
01:41:35,167 --> 01:41:37,886
in the area know
that Pan Am will be initiating

2239
01:41:37,927 --> 01:41:39,883
a new recruiting program
this year.

2240
01:41:39,927 --> 01:41:43,044
I'II, uh, be stopping
by your campus tomorrow morning.

2241
01:41:43,087 --> 01:41:45,999
Thank you all very much
for coming.

2242
01:41:46,047 --> 01:41:47,162
At the end of the day

2243
01:41:47,207 --> 01:41:50,199
I'll be choosing eight
young ladies to be a part of...

2244
01:41:50,247 --> 01:41:51,760
(<i>cheering and laughter</i>)

2245
01:41:51,807 --> 01:41:54,480
...Pan Am's future stewardess
flight crew program.

2246
01:41:54,527 --> 01:41:56,995
Now, these eight young ladies
will accompany me

2247
01:41:57,047 --> 01:41:59,959
on a two-month public relations
tour through Europe.

2248
01:42:00,007 --> 01:42:01,235
(<i>women squealing</i>)

2249
01:42:01,287 --> 01:42:03,847
They will discover firsthand
what it takes

2250
01:42:03,887 --> 01:42:05,878
to be a Pan American stewardess.

2251
01:42:05,927 --> 01:42:07,679
(<i>cheering</i>)

2252
01:42:07,727 --> 01:42:10,161
HANRATTY:
Give me at least two men...

2253
01:42:10,207 --> 01:42:12,675
Nah, one man
per every two counters.

2254
01:42:12,727 --> 01:42:14,001
- Mm-hmm.
- All right?

2255
01:42:14,047 --> 01:42:15,480
Amdursky?

2256
01:42:15,527 --> 01:42:17,404
Yeah?

2257
01:42:17,447 --> 01:42:19,483
Make sure your uniforms
are covering

2258
01:42:19,527 --> 01:42:21,404
the sidewalk entrances
and exits.

2259
01:42:21,447 --> 01:42:24,757
Hey... let's have, uh, periodic
sweeps of the men's lav.

2260
01:42:24,807 --> 01:42:27,116
You, here.

2261
01:42:27,167 --> 01:42:30,796
What qualifies me
to be a future stewardess?

2262
01:42:30,847 --> 01:42:33,281
Well, I think
that I'm really friendly

2263
01:42:33,327 --> 01:42:34,965
and I can really help out

2264
01:42:35,007 --> 01:42:38,522
and, um, make people
feel welcome on the plane and...

2265
01:42:38,567 --> 01:42:40,956
We'll be traveling
at 6,000 miles per hour

2266
01:42:41,007 --> 01:42:42,599
at an altitude of 300 feet.

2267
01:42:42,647 --> 01:42:47,596
All my bags are packed,
I'm ready to go...

2268
01:42:47,647 --> 01:42:49,797
(<i>playing dramatic piano intro</i>)

2269
01:42:49,847 --> 01:42:51,166
Ilene Anderson.

2270
01:42:51,207 --> 01:42:53,357
(<i>squealing and applause</i>)

2271
01:42:53,407 --> 01:42:58,322
(<i>pianist playing</i>
<i>"Come Fly With Me"</i>)

2272
01:42:58,367 --> 01:43:00,517
Miggy Acker.

2273
01:43:00,567 --> 01:43:02,956
(<i>excited squealing</i>)

2274
01:43:04,567 --> 01:43:07,035
Debra Jo McMillan.

2275
01:43:12,607 --> 01:43:14,757
Candy Heston.

2276
01:43:14,807 --> 01:43:22,282
FRANK SINATRA:
Come fly with me,
let's fly, let's fly away

2277
01:43:22,327 --> 01:43:25,319
If you can use
some exotic booze

2278
01:43:25,367 --> 01:43:28,723
There's a bar in far Bombay

2279
01:43:28,767 --> 01:43:36,037
Come fly with me,
let's fly, let's fly away

2280
01:43:36,087 --> 01:43:39,682
Come fly with me,
let's float down to Peru

2281
01:43:42,527 --> 01:43:45,485
In Ilama land
there's a one-man band

2282
01:43:45,527 --> 01:43:48,485
And he'll toot his flute
for you

2283
01:43:48,527 --> 01:43:50,245
(<i>appreciative whistle</i>)

2284
01:43:50,287 --> 01:43:51,356
Come fly with me...

2285
01:43:51,407 --> 01:43:52,476
Hi.

2286
01:43:52,527 --> 01:43:54,995
...Let's take off
in the blue

2287
01:43:55,047 --> 01:43:58,357
Once I get you up there

2288
01:43:58,407 --> 01:44:00,557
Where the air is rarefied

2289
01:44:00,607 --> 01:44:02,757
(<i>wolf whistle</i>)

2290
01:44:02,807 --> 01:44:08,677
We'll just glide starry-eyed

2291
01:44:08,727 --> 01:44:11,560
Once I get you up there...

2292
01:44:11,607 --> 01:44:13,006
You see that blonde out front?

2293
01:44:13,047 --> 01:44:14,116
I should have been a pilot.

2294
01:44:14,167 --> 01:44:15,885
Exactly.

2295
01:44:15,927 --> 01:44:17,280
WOMAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
Mr. Carl Hanratty

2296
01:44:17,327 --> 01:44:18,680
please pick up
the courtesy telephone.

2297
01:44:18,727 --> 01:44:19,876
Hanratty.

2298
01:44:19,927 --> 01:44:21,963
AMDURSKY:
Carl, your walkie-talkie
wasn't working.

2299
01:44:22,007 --> 01:44:23,360
There's a guy
in a Pan Am uniform

2300
01:44:23,407 --> 01:44:25,967
sitting in a white Coupe DeVille
out in front of Terminal J.

2301
01:44:26,007 --> 01:44:27,076
That's the charter terminal.

2302
01:44:27,127 --> 01:44:28,321
Can you get a look at his face?

2303
01:44:28,367 --> 01:44:29,482
He's got his pilot's cap on.

2304
01:44:29,527 --> 01:44:30,676
Carl, I think it's him!

2305
01:44:30,727 --> 01:44:32,843
...Just say the words,
and we'll beat the birds

2306
01:44:32,887 --> 01:44:34,320
Down to Acapulco Bay...

2307
01:44:34,367 --> 01:44:35,641
(<i>siren blaring</i>)

2308
01:44:35,687 --> 01:44:37,086
Watch out, watch out,
watch out!

2309
01:44:37,127 --> 01:44:40,836
...It's perfect for a flying
honeymoon, they say...

2310
01:44:40,887 --> 01:44:42,639
(<i>agents shouting</i>)

2311
01:44:42,687 --> 01:44:44,120
Out of the car, Frank.

2312
01:44:44,167 --> 01:44:45,646
(<i>patrol cars' tires squealing</i>)

2313
01:44:45,687 --> 01:44:46,642
Frank?!

2314
01:44:46,687 --> 01:44:48,678
Step out of the car!

2315
01:44:48,727 --> 01:44:50,922
Keep your hands
where I can see 'em.

2316
01:44:50,967 --> 01:44:52,605
Don't shoot me!
I'm just a driver.

2317
01:44:52,647 --> 01:44:54,638
A man paid me $100
to wear this uniform

2318
01:44:54,687 --> 01:44:55,756
and pick someone up
at the airport.

2319
01:44:55,807 --> 01:44:56,762
Who you picking up?

2320
01:44:57,727 --> 01:44:58,876
Hey!

2321
01:45:02,327 --> 01:45:07,321
Pack up, let's fly away.

2322
01:45:10,007 --> 01:45:12,567
(<i>engine roaring</i>)

2323
01:45:18,927 --> 01:45:21,964
Seven months later

2324
01:45:22,007 --> 01:45:23,520
HANRATTY:
South America, Australia

2325
01:45:23,567 --> 01:45:24,477
Singapore, Egypt.

2326
01:45:24,527 --> 01:45:26,279
The kid's gone
completely out of control.

2327
01:45:26,327 --> 01:45:27,396
Why wasn't I called?

2328
01:45:27,447 --> 01:45:28,846
FOX:
Nobody was called, sir.

2329
01:45:28,887 --> 01:45:31,765
The banks didn't know what
was happening till last week.

2330
01:45:31,807 --> 01:45:32,922
That's impossible.

2331
01:45:32,967 --> 01:45:34,639
They didn't call
'cause it's not counterfeiting.

2332
01:45:34,687 --> 01:45:36,200
- It's something else.
- Well, what is he doing?

2333
01:45:36,247 --> 01:45:37,316
He's making real checks, sir.

2334
01:45:37,367 --> 01:45:38,277
These are so perfect

2335
01:45:38,327 --> 01:45:39,840
the airline didn't know
the difference.

2336
01:45:39,887 --> 01:45:41,559
Last check was cashed
in Madrid a week ago.

2337
01:45:41,607 --> 01:45:42,722
My guess is he's still there.

2338
01:45:42,767 --> 01:45:44,041
We have to leave now, sir.
Today.

2339
01:45:44,087 --> 01:45:45,315
Go where?

2340
01:45:45,367 --> 01:45:46,925
Spain? You want to go to Spain?

2341
01:45:46,967 --> 01:45:48,286
Well, eventually,
he's got to go back

2342
01:45:48,327 --> 01:45:49,476
to where the checks
were printed.

2343
01:45:49,527 --> 01:45:51,404
I think that's why
he's moving back through Europe.

2344
01:45:51,447 --> 01:45:53,039
Look at the map, sir.
He's making a circle.

2345
01:45:53,087 --> 01:45:54,076
He's running out of checks.

2346
01:45:54,127 --> 01:45:55,480
I know it's a...
it's a long shot, sir

2347
01:45:55,527 --> 01:45:57,882
but if we track him from Madrid,
sir, we could still catch him.

2348
01:45:57,927 --> 01:45:59,645
I'm sorry, Carl,
if you couldn't catch him here

2349
01:45:59,687 --> 01:46:01,006
you're not going
to catch him there.

2350
01:46:01,047 --> 01:46:02,844
But, sir, we're going
to let him get away.

2351
01:46:02,887 --> 01:46:06,323
No, Carl, you let him get away.

2352
01:46:15,407 --> 01:46:18,285
(<i>tapping map</i>)

2353
01:46:45,447 --> 01:46:50,885
A perfect one-16th
all the way around.

2354
01:46:50,927 --> 01:46:52,519
Hmm!

2355
01:46:52,567 --> 01:46:55,206
Color separation is flawless.

2356
01:46:57,367 --> 01:46:59,403
There's no bleeding. Hmm.

2357
01:46:59,447 --> 01:47:01,961
Nobody does work like this
in the States.

2358
01:47:02,007 --> 01:47:03,235
Nobody but us.

2359
01:47:03,287 --> 01:47:05,005
HANRATTY:
Where was it printed?

2360
01:47:05,047 --> 01:47:07,197
(<i>chuckling</i>):
It was printed on a monster...

2361
01:47:07,247 --> 01:47:08,157
A monster.

2362
01:47:08,207 --> 01:47:09,640
...a Heidelberg, an Istra...

2363
01:47:09,687 --> 01:47:10,756
Heidelberg.

2364
01:47:10,807 --> 01:47:12,365
...a dinosaur, four colors.

2365
01:47:12,407 --> 01:47:13,840
You can smell the weight.

2366
01:47:13,887 --> 01:47:15,400
Two tons, without the ink.

2367
01:47:15,447 --> 01:47:16,800
(<i>inhales, clears throat</i>)

2368
01:47:16,847 --> 01:47:18,803
Where do they do printing
like this?

2369
01:47:18,847 --> 01:47:20,405
Germany, Great Britain...

2370
01:47:20,447 --> 01:47:21,357
France.

2371
01:47:21,407 --> 01:47:24,046
BOTH PRINTERS:
France!

2372
01:47:24,087 --> 01:47:26,157
France. Frank's mother said
the name of a village in France

2373
01:47:26,207 --> 01:47:27,322
where they didn't have Sara Lee.

2374
01:47:27,367 --> 01:47:28,846
The village where
she met Frank's father.

2375
01:47:28,887 --> 01:47:30,240
Oh, yeah,
I don't remember, uh...

2376
01:47:30,287 --> 01:47:32,118
It started with an M.
It was, uh, "Mont" something.

2377
01:47:32,167 --> 01:47:33,077
"Mont." Mr. Fox?

2378
01:47:33,127 --> 01:47:34,037
Uh, yes, yes.

2379
01:47:34,087 --> 01:47:35,805
Question: "You met your husband
during the war?"

2380
01:47:35,847 --> 01:47:37,644
Answer: "Yes, I lived
in a small village in France.

2381
01:47:37,687 --> 01:47:38,881
Yeah, right.

2382
01:47:38,927 --> 01:47:41,157
"The kind of place where
they never heard of Sara Lee."

2383
01:47:41,207 --> 01:47:43,437
Tell me you wrote down the name
of the village, Mr. Fox.

2384
01:47:43,487 --> 01:47:46,638
Montrichard.

2385
01:47:46,687 --> 01:47:48,803
CHORUS (<i>in distance</i>):
Laeti triumphantes

2386
01:47:48,847 --> 01:47:51,077
Montrichard, France
Christmas Eve 1967

2387
01:47:51,127 --> 01:47:55,405
Venite, venite

2388
01:47:55,447 --> 01:48:00,840
In Bethlehem

2389
01:48:00,887 --> 01:48:05,324
Natum videte

2390
01:48:05,367 --> 01:48:10,122
Regem angelorum

2391
01:48:10,167 --> 01:48:19,883
Venite adoremus,
Venite adoremus

2392
01:48:19,927 --> 01:48:22,077
Venite...

2393
01:48:22,127 --> 01:48:24,880
(<i>rhythmic clattering</i>)

2394
01:48:36,407 --> 01:48:37,522
(<i>bell ringing</i>)

2395
01:48:37,567 --> 01:48:39,159
(<i>thumping and fluttering</i>)

2396
01:48:39,207 --> 01:48:40,322
(<i>clattering slows</i>)

2397
01:48:40,367 --> 01:48:41,277
Carl?

2398
01:48:41,327 --> 01:48:42,442
Carl!

2399
01:48:43,847 --> 01:48:45,200
Merry Christmas!

2400
01:48:45,247 --> 01:48:47,966
How is it that we're always
talking on Christmas, Carl?

2401
01:48:48,007 --> 01:48:49,759
Every Christmas
I'm talking to you!

2402
01:48:49,807 --> 01:48:50,922
(<i>laughing</i>)

2403
01:48:50,967 --> 01:48:52,719
Put your shirt on, Frank.
You're under arrest.

2404
01:48:52,767 --> 01:48:54,678
Hey, are you hungry?
Do you want some beans, Carl?

2405
01:48:54,727 --> 01:48:56,080
They got the best
French beans here.

2406
01:48:56,127 --> 01:48:57,037
Here, give these a try.

2407
01:48:57,087 --> 01:48:58,918
There's two dozen French
police officers outside.

2408
01:48:58,967 --> 01:49:00,525
Carl, I gotta tell you,
they're delicious.

2409
01:49:00,567 --> 01:49:01,636
They wanted to bring you in.

2410
01:49:01,687 --> 01:49:02,802
You want a bite?

2411
01:49:02,847 --> 01:49:04,280
But they needed the help
of an American.

2412
01:49:04,327 --> 01:49:05,476
Are you hungry?
You want a bite?

2413
01:49:05,527 --> 01:49:07,085
But I told them
I wouldn't bring them to you

2414
01:49:07,127 --> 01:49:08,719
unless I could put the cuffs
on you myself.

2415
01:49:08,767 --> 01:49:10,280
Well, you have a gun?
You have a gun?

2416
01:49:10,327 --> 01:49:11,396
- No gun?
- No.

2417
01:49:11,447 --> 01:49:12,436
No gun.

2418
01:49:14,047 --> 01:49:15,639
And-and you're...
and you're telling me what?

2419
01:49:15,687 --> 01:49:17,120
There's, uh,
there's uh... (<i>chuckles</i>)

2420
01:49:17,167 --> 01:49:18,964
There's two dozen
French police officers out there

2421
01:49:19,007 --> 01:49:19,996
right now on Christmas Eve?

2422
01:49:20,047 --> 01:49:21,162
That's what you're telling me?

2423
01:49:21,207 --> 01:49:22,401
Yeah.

2424
01:49:22,447 --> 01:49:23,721
(<i>chuckling</i>):
All right, all right.

2425
01:49:23,767 --> 01:49:25,405
Well, there's no windows here.

2426
01:49:25,447 --> 01:49:27,881
I'm going to take a look
out the front door.

2427
01:49:27,927 --> 01:49:28,996
No! No!

2428
01:49:29,047 --> 01:49:31,641
I told them I'd walk out first
and give a signal.

2429
01:49:31,687 --> 01:49:33,040
Here, you can
put these on yourself.

2430
01:49:33,087 --> 01:49:34,600
No, I can't do that!
I can't do that.

2431
01:49:34,647 --> 01:49:35,716
You know why?

2432
01:49:35,767 --> 01:49:36,802
(<i>panting</i>)

2433
01:49:36,847 --> 01:49:38,280
'Cause I think
you're full of shit.

2434
01:49:38,327 --> 01:49:40,636
I don't... I don't think
there's anyone else out there.

2435
01:49:40,687 --> 01:49:42,518
I think... I think
it's just me and you.

2436
01:49:42,567 --> 01:49:43,761
That's right.

2437
01:49:43,807 --> 01:49:45,684
I think it's just me and you,
and you know what?

2438
01:49:45,727 --> 01:49:47,365
You're going to have
to catch me yourself!

2439
01:49:47,407 --> 01:49:49,967
I wo... we don't have time
for this.

2440
01:49:50,007 --> 01:49:52,077
Ah, that's good. That's good.

2441
01:49:52,127 --> 01:49:54,766
Tell me what you want me to see,
huh?

2442
01:49:54,807 --> 01:49:55,762
I wouldn't lie to you.

2443
01:49:55,807 --> 01:49:57,240
Look, you're wearing
a wedding ring.

2444
01:49:57,287 --> 01:49:58,766
You're wearing
a wedding ring, Carl!

2445
01:49:58,807 --> 01:49:59,842
You lied to me about that!

2446
01:49:59,887 --> 01:50:01,240
Didn't you lie about that?!

2447
01:50:01,287 --> 01:50:02,879
You asked me if I had a family.

2448
01:50:02,927 --> 01:50:04,406
I did, but I don't anymore.

2449
01:50:04,447 --> 01:50:06,278
(<i>phone ringing</i>)

2450
01:50:06,327 --> 01:50:08,602
(<i>anxious breathing</i>)

2451
01:50:10,807 --> 01:50:12,843
(<i>ringing continues</i>)

2452
01:50:12,887 --> 01:50:14,718
Yes? No, no, no,
there is no problem.

2453
01:50:14,767 --> 01:50:16,166
We're coming out right now.

2454
01:50:16,207 --> 01:50:18,084
(<i>laughing</i>)

2455
01:50:18,127 --> 01:50:19,765
Whoa, that was good.
That was good.

2456
01:50:19,807 --> 01:50:21,684
What, did you...
you pay some hotel desk clerk

2457
01:50:21,727 --> 01:50:23,763
to make that call for you,
is that what you did?

2458
01:50:23,807 --> 01:50:24,717
It was Captain Luc.

2459
01:50:24,767 --> 01:50:25,882
I've got one minute
to bring you out.

2460
01:50:25,927 --> 01:50:27,246
Captain Luc? Captain Luc!

2461
01:50:27,287 --> 01:50:28,197
Ooh, Captain Luc.

2462
01:50:28,247 --> 01:50:29,441
Well, Carl, I gotta say

2463
01:50:29,487 --> 01:50:31,478
that-that sounds
pretty official to me

2464
01:50:31,527 --> 01:50:33,597
but like I said, I...
I think it's just

2465
01:50:33,647 --> 01:50:34,921
me and you here,
it's me and you.

2466
01:50:34,967 --> 01:50:36,320
So you're going to have
to catch me.

2467
01:50:36,367 --> 01:50:37,277
Frank. Frank!

2468
01:50:37,327 --> 01:50:39,124
You have to trust me on this!

2469
01:50:39,167 --> 01:50:41,806
These people
have been embarrassed, Frank.

2470
01:50:41,847 --> 01:50:42,916
They're angry.

2471
01:50:42,967 --> 01:50:44,605
You rob their banks,
you steal their money

2472
01:50:44,647 --> 01:50:45,682
you live in their country.

2473
01:50:45,727 --> 01:50:47,445
I told you this was
what was going to happen

2474
01:50:47,487 --> 01:50:49,159
that there was no other way
for it to end.

2475
01:50:49,207 --> 01:50:51,846
Don't make a mistake!

2476
01:50:51,887 --> 01:50:53,002
That's good.

2477
01:50:53,047 --> 01:50:55,242
That's good, Carl, you know?

2478
01:50:55,287 --> 01:50:56,197
Keep pushing that lie.

2479
01:50:56,247 --> 01:50:57,157
Keep pushing it.

2480
01:50:57,207 --> 01:50:58,765
Keep pushing
till you make it true.

2481
01:50:58,807 --> 01:51:01,196
They're going to kill you!

2482
01:51:01,247 --> 01:51:03,807
You walk out that door,
they're going to kill you.

2483
01:51:03,847 --> 01:51:05,758
(<i>panting</i>)

2484
01:51:08,567 --> 01:51:10,683
Is that the truth?

2485
01:51:14,167 --> 01:51:16,397
Yeah.

2486
01:51:20,087 --> 01:51:22,555
You have any children, Carl?

2487
01:51:22,607 --> 01:51:26,156
I have a four-year-old daughter.

2488
01:51:26,207 --> 01:51:28,721
You swear on your daughter?

2489
01:51:30,647 --> 01:51:33,002
You swear?

2490
01:51:37,007 --> 01:51:40,204
You swear?

2491
01:51:40,247 --> 01:51:42,317
(<i>handcuffs clacking</i>)

2492
01:51:50,047 --> 01:51:54,438
CHORUS:
Redit ce chant melodieux

2493
01:51:54,487 --> 01:52:02,121
Gloria

2494
01:52:02,167 --> 01:52:05,603
In excelsius Deo

2495
01:52:05,647 --> 01:52:08,639
Gloria...

2496
01:52:08,687 --> 01:52:10,757
That was really good, Carl.

2497
01:52:10,807 --> 01:52:13,560
(<i>car approaching</i>)

2498
01:52:13,607 --> 01:52:15,438
(<i>sirens blaring</i>)

2499
01:52:15,487 --> 01:52:17,478
(<i>chorus continues singing</i>)

2500
01:52:17,527 --> 01:52:18,755
(<i>tires screeching</i>)

2501
01:52:18,807 --> 01:52:20,001
(<i>officer shouting in French</i>)

2502
01:52:20,047 --> 01:52:20,957
I have him in custody.

2503
01:52:21,007 --> 01:52:22,156
I got him.

2504
01:52:22,207 --> 01:52:23,799
I got him! It's all right!

2505
01:52:23,847 --> 01:52:25,166
(<i>shouting continues</i>)

2506
01:52:25,207 --> 01:52:26,276
It's all right!

2507
01:52:26,327 --> 01:52:27,965
I got him!

2508
01:52:28,007 --> 01:52:28,996
(<i>speaking in French</i>)

2509
01:52:29,047 --> 01:52:30,719
(<i>officer shouting excitedly</i>)

2510
01:52:30,767 --> 01:52:33,122
Hey, I want it...
I want it on the record.

2511
01:52:33,167 --> 01:52:35,727
Frank Abagnale surrendered
of his own accord.

2512
01:52:35,767 --> 01:52:37,997
Understood? Understood?

2513
01:52:38,047 --> 01:52:38,957
Where are you taking him?

2514
01:52:39,007 --> 01:52:39,917
(<i>speaking in French</i>)

2515
01:52:39,967 --> 01:52:40,877
I'm... I'm supposed to go.

2516
01:52:40,927 --> 01:52:42,599
Where are you taking him?

2517
01:52:42,647 --> 01:52:43,841
Let me in the...

2518
01:52:43,887 --> 01:52:44,797
Let me in the car!

2519
01:52:44,847 --> 01:52:45,836
(<i>shouting continues</i>)

2520
01:52:45,887 --> 01:52:48,003
Hey! Let me in the car!

2521
01:52:48,047 --> 01:52:49,162
Gloria...

2522
01:52:49,207 --> 01:52:50,276
(<i>engine starts</i>)

2523
01:52:50,327 --> 01:52:51,442
Don't worry, Frank!

2524
01:52:51,487 --> 01:52:53,443
I'll have you extradited
back to the United States.

2525
01:52:53,487 --> 01:52:54,476
Don't worry.

2526
01:52:54,527 --> 01:52:57,041
(<i>siren wailing</i>)

2527
01:52:59,167 --> 01:53:07,404
Gloria

2528
01:53:09,567 --> 01:53:14,118
In excelsius Deo.

2529
01:53:14,167 --> 01:53:16,920
Carl...

2530
01:53:16,967 --> 01:53:19,356
Carl, you have to remember

2531
01:53:19,407 --> 01:53:22,922
to let me call my father
when we land.

2532
01:53:22,967 --> 01:53:24,798
I just want to,
I want to talk to him

2533
01:53:24,847 --> 01:53:27,759
before he sees me on television
or something like that.

2534
01:53:37,207 --> 01:53:38,720
Carl, look.

2535
01:53:38,767 --> 01:53:40,723
That's LaGuardia right there.

2536
01:53:40,767 --> 01:53:42,405
Runway 4-4.

2537
01:53:42,447 --> 01:53:45,007
Frank, your father is dead.

2538
01:53:45,047 --> 01:53:46,924
I'm sorry.

2539
01:53:46,967 --> 01:53:50,403
I didn't want to say anything
till we got closer to home.

2540
01:53:50,447 --> 01:53:54,963
He-He... He fell down some steps
at Grand Central Station

2541
01:53:55,007 --> 01:53:56,963
trying to catch a train.

2542
01:53:57,007 --> 01:53:59,237
I didn't want to be the one
to tell you.

2543
01:53:59,287 --> 01:54:02,404
You're lying, right?

2544
01:54:02,447 --> 01:54:04,642
You said I could talk to him.

2545
01:54:04,687 --> 01:54:05,597
Carl, who are you to...

2546
01:54:05,647 --> 01:54:07,399
who are you to say
something like that, huh?

2547
01:54:07,447 --> 01:54:09,005
Who are you
to say something like that?

2548
01:54:09,047 --> 01:54:10,241
You said I could talk to him.

2549
01:54:10,287 --> 01:54:12,164
He fell, and he...
and he broke his neck.

2550
01:54:12,207 --> 01:54:14,596
I'm sorry.

2551
01:54:14,647 --> 01:54:17,161
I'm really sorry.

2552
01:54:23,927 --> 01:54:26,805
(<i>panting</i>)

2553
01:54:26,847 --> 01:54:28,121
(<i>hits seat</i>)

2554
01:54:28,167 --> 01:54:29,725
(<i>sobbing</i>):
Goddamn it!

2555
01:54:29,767 --> 01:54:31,723
Carl, I'm going to be sick!

2556
01:54:31,767 --> 01:54:33,166
- (<i>people muttering</i>)
- It's all right.

2557
01:54:33,207 --> 01:54:34,162
It's all right. It's okay.

2558
01:54:34,207 --> 01:54:35,526
Carl, I got to go
to the bathroom.

2559
01:54:35,567 --> 01:54:36,477
I'm going to be sick.

2560
01:54:36,527 --> 01:54:38,245
Sure.
Let's go in the bathroom.

2561
01:54:39,607 --> 01:54:41,518
(<i>panting</i>)

2562
01:54:45,007 --> 01:54:46,281
Goddamn it!

2563
01:54:46,327 --> 01:54:50,115
(<i>sobbing</i>)

2564
01:54:50,167 --> 01:54:51,646
(<i>pounding</i>)

2565
01:54:51,687 --> 01:54:53,040
(<i>murmuring</i>)

2566
01:54:53,087 --> 01:54:55,521
(<i>panting</i>)

2567
01:54:55,567 --> 01:54:57,558
(<i>panting slows</i>)

2568
01:54:58,887 --> 01:55:00,718
(<i>Frank panting</i>)

2569
01:55:03,167 --> 01:55:06,045
(<i>whispering</i>):
Oh, Daddy...

2570
01:55:08,567 --> 01:55:09,966
You'll have take your seat, sir.

2571
01:55:10,007 --> 01:55:11,520
I've told you twice.
We're landing.

2572
01:55:11,567 --> 01:55:12,920
- Sorry. Thank you...
- All of you.

2573
01:55:12,967 --> 01:55:14,116
Frank! Come on now.

2574
01:55:14,167 --> 01:55:15,646
- Frank?
- We're landing in six minutes.

2575
01:55:15,687 --> 01:55:17,166
All of you need to be
in your seats

2576
01:55:17,207 --> 01:55:19,402
- with your seat belts fastened.
- Frank, open the door!

2577
01:55:19,447 --> 01:55:21,005
Frank!

2578
01:55:22,807 --> 01:55:24,365
- You do it.
- Yeah.

2579
01:55:36,047 --> 01:55:38,515
(<i>engines decelerating</i>)

2580
01:55:44,807 --> 01:55:47,116
(<i>grunting</i>)

2581
01:55:49,847 --> 01:55:51,075
(<i>frustrated sigh</i>)

2582
01:55:51,127 --> 01:55:52,446
(<i>grunting</i>)

2583
01:55:52,487 --> 01:55:54,364
Frank! Frank!

2584
01:55:54,407 --> 01:55:56,363
(<i>engines roaring</i>)

2585
01:55:56,407 --> 01:55:58,477
(<i>tires squealing</i>)

2586
01:55:58,527 --> 01:56:01,041
HANRATTY:
All right, remain seated,
everyone, please.

2587
01:56:01,087 --> 01:56:02,805
FBI. Stay seated.
FBI. Stay seated.

2588
01:56:02,847 --> 01:56:05,759
(<i>engines whining</i>)

2589
01:56:10,887 --> 01:56:12,240
- Please remain seated!
- Stay seated.

2590
01:56:12,287 --> 01:56:13,481
STEWARDESS:
You must stay seated

2591
01:56:13,527 --> 01:56:15,961
until the aircraft
has come to a complete stop.

2592
01:56:16,007 --> 01:56:17,486
HANRATTY:
God almighty.

2593
01:56:17,527 --> 01:56:21,122
NAT KING COLE:
Chestnuts roasting
on an open fire...

2594
01:56:21,167 --> 01:56:24,000
(<i>panting</i>)

2595
01:56:24,047 --> 01:56:30,964
Jack Frost nipping
at your nose

2596
01:56:31,007 --> 01:56:36,127
Yuletide carols
being sung by a choir

2597
01:56:36,167 --> 01:56:41,605
And folks dressed up
like Eskimos

2598
01:56:41,647 --> 01:56:44,480
Everybody knows

2599
01:56:44,527 --> 01:56:49,521
A turkey and some mistletoe

2600
01:56:49,567 --> 01:56:54,038
Help to make
the season bright

2601
01:56:54,087 --> 01:56:56,237
(<i>quietly blowing notes</i>)

2602
01:56:56,287 --> 01:57:00,565
Tiny tots with their eyes
all aglow

2603
01:57:00,607 --> 01:57:04,441
Will find it hard
to sleep tonight...

2604
01:57:04,487 --> 01:57:06,364
What's your name?

2605
01:57:06,407 --> 01:57:07,396
(<i>blows note</i>)

2606
01:57:07,447 --> 01:57:09,403
They know that Santa's
on his way...

2607
01:57:09,447 --> 01:57:12,803
Where's your mommy?

2608
01:57:12,847 --> 01:57:17,238
...He's loaded lots of toys
and goodies on his sleigh

2609
01:57:17,287 --> 01:57:20,040
(<i>blows note</i>)

2610
01:57:20,087 --> 01:57:25,286
And every mother's child
is gonna spy

2611
01:57:25,327 --> 01:57:27,716
To see if reindeer
really know how to fly...

2612
01:57:27,767 --> 01:57:30,725
(<i>brakes squeaking</i>)

2613
01:57:30,767 --> 01:57:35,716
And so I'm offering
this simple phrase...

2614
01:57:35,767 --> 01:57:38,725
(<i>men shouting indistinctly</i>)

2615
01:57:38,767 --> 01:57:44,876
To kids from one to 92

2616
01:57:44,927 --> 01:57:48,237
Although it's been said
many times

2617
01:57:48,287 --> 01:57:51,563
Many ways:
"Merry Christmas..."

2618
01:57:51,607 --> 01:57:53,245
Hands behind your head!

2619
01:57:53,287 --> 01:57:55,164
...To you.

2620
01:57:55,207 --> 01:57:56,560
Carl, get me in the car,
please.

2621
01:57:56,607 --> 01:57:59,644
Get me in the car.

2622
01:57:59,687 --> 01:58:01,564
HANRATTY:
Put him in.

2623
01:58:01,607 --> 01:58:04,440
(<i>piano playing interlude</i>
<i>in "The Christmas Song"</i>)

2624
01:58:04,487 --> 01:58:06,398
(<i>handcuffs latching</i>)

2625
01:58:16,927 --> 01:58:20,363
JUDGE:
<i>Taking into account</i>
<i>the gravity of these crimes</i>

2626
01:58:20,407 --> 01:58:24,082
<i>your history of bold</i>
<i>and elusive behavior</i>

2627
01:58:24,127 --> 01:58:26,402
<i>and your complete lack</i>
<i>of respect</i>

2628
01:58:26,447 --> 01:58:28,756
<i>for the laws</i>
<i>of the United States</i>

2629
01:58:28,807 --> 01:58:31,799
<i>I have no choice</i>
<i>but to ignore your request</i>

2630
01:58:31,847 --> 01:58:33,678
<i>to be treated as a minor</i>

2631
01:58:33,727 --> 01:58:35,479
<i>and sentence you to 12 years</i>

2632
01:58:35,527 --> 01:58:38,599
<i>in Atlanta's</i>
<i>maximum security prison</i>

2633
01:58:38,647 --> 01:58:41,844
<i>and recommend strongly</i>
<i>that you be kept in isolation</i>

2634
01:58:41,887 --> 01:58:43,878
<i>for the entirety</i>
<i>of that sentence.</i>

2635
01:58:43,927 --> 01:58:47,237
..."Merry Christmas to you."

2636
01:58:47,287 --> 01:58:50,723
(<i>song ends with guitar playing</i>
<i>"Jingle Bells" riff</i>)

2637
01:58:55,927 --> 01:58:57,645
Use that door over there.

2638
01:58:57,687 --> 01:59:00,042
(<i>phone ringing</i>)

2639
01:59:00,087 --> 01:59:03,045
(<i>indistinct voices</i>)

2640
01:59:03,087 --> 01:59:04,964
PRISONER:
...and give everyone my love.

2641
01:59:05,007 --> 01:59:06,599
I think about them all the time.

2642
01:59:16,807 --> 01:59:18,877
(<i>indistinct conversations</i>
<i>in distance</i>)

2643
01:59:23,127 --> 01:59:24,355
(<i>sighs deeply</i>)

2644
01:59:24,407 --> 01:59:26,682
Merry Christmas, Frank.

2645
01:59:28,967 --> 01:59:31,481
Hey, I got you
some comic books here.

2646
01:59:37,927 --> 01:59:39,121
How's your daughter?

2647
01:59:39,167 --> 01:59:40,361
What was her name?

2648
01:59:40,407 --> 01:59:41,317
Grace.

2649
01:59:41,367 --> 01:59:42,595
Well... I don't know.

2650
01:59:42,647 --> 01:59:44,717
She lives with her mother
in Chicago

2651
01:59:44,767 --> 01:59:46,644
and I don't get to see her much.

2652
01:59:48,087 --> 01:59:49,600
What's in the briefcase?

2653
01:59:49,647 --> 01:59:51,524
Oh. I'm on my way
to the airport.

2654
01:59:51,567 --> 01:59:53,444
It's a paperhanger

2655
01:59:53,487 --> 01:59:55,603
who's working his way
through Minnesota.

2656
01:59:55,647 --> 01:59:56,966
(<i>chuckling</i>)

2657
01:59:57,007 --> 02:00:00,363
Aw, geez, he's...
he's driving us crazy.

2658
02:00:00,407 --> 02:00:01,920
You got any of the checks?

2659
02:00:01,967 --> 02:00:04,356
Yeah, yeah, I got a...
a counterfeit that he drew

2660
02:00:04,407 --> 02:00:06,125
on the Great Lakes
Savings and Loan.

2661
02:00:06,167 --> 02:00:07,998
See, he's just using
a stencil machine

2662
02:00:08,047 --> 02:00:09,480
and an Underwood.

2663
02:00:09,527 --> 02:00:12,041
Yeah, it's a teller at the bank.

2664
02:00:12,087 --> 02:00:13,361
Say again?

2665
02:00:13,407 --> 02:00:14,920
L-It's definitely a teller,
Carl.

2666
02:00:14,967 --> 02:00:16,958
I mean, banks,
they always use hand-stamps

2667
02:00:17,007 --> 02:00:18,406
for the dates, see.

2668
02:00:18,447 --> 02:00:20,085
They get used
over and over again

2669
02:00:20,127 --> 02:00:21,446
so they always get worn out

2670
02:00:21,487 --> 02:00:23,284
and the numbers
are always cracking.

2671
02:00:23,327 --> 02:00:26,922
The sixes and the nines...
see, they go first.

2672
02:00:28,847 --> 02:00:30,644
Thanks.

2673
02:00:30,687 --> 02:00:32,598
(<i>buzzer sounding</i>)

2674
02:00:35,087 --> 02:00:36,645
MAN:
<i>I'd like you to take a look</i>

2675
02:00:36,687 --> 02:00:37,961
<i>at something for me.</i>

2676
02:00:42,607 --> 02:00:44,723
Tell me what you think.

2677
02:00:44,767 --> 02:00:47,156
(<i>clears throat</i>)

2678
02:00:47,207 --> 02:00:48,720
That's a fake.

2679
02:00:48,767 --> 02:00:50,200
How do you know?

2680
02:00:50,247 --> 02:00:51,362
You haven't looked at it.

2681
02:00:51,407 --> 02:00:53,796
Well, there's
no perforated edge, right?

2682
02:00:53,847 --> 02:00:56,725
I mean, this... this check
was hand-cut, not fed.

2683
02:00:56,767 --> 02:00:58,883
Yeah...

2684
02:00:58,927 --> 02:01:00,121
Paper is double-bonded

2685
02:01:00,167 --> 02:01:02,397
much too heavy
to be a bank check.

2686
02:01:02,447 --> 02:01:06,235
Magnetic ink, it's, uh,
raised against my fingers

2687
02:01:06,287 --> 02:01:07,515
instead of flat.

2688
02:01:07,567 --> 02:01:08,636
(<i>sniffing</i>)

2689
02:01:08,687 --> 02:01:10,086
And this doesn't smell
like MICR.

2690
02:01:10,127 --> 02:01:11,116
It's some kind of a...

2691
02:01:11,167 --> 02:01:12,839
you know,
some kind of a drafting ink.

2692
02:01:12,887 --> 02:01:15,037
You know, the kind you get
at a stationery store.

2693
02:01:15,087 --> 02:01:16,361
(<i>clears throat</i>)

2694
02:01:18,847 --> 02:01:20,758
(<i>paper rustling</i>)

2695
02:01:20,807 --> 02:01:22,559
Frank...

2696
02:01:22,607 --> 02:01:24,438
would you be interested
in working

2697
02:01:24,487 --> 02:01:26,443
with the FBI's
Financial Crimes Unit?

2698
02:01:26,487 --> 02:01:28,364
(<i>shuffles cards</i>)

2699
02:01:28,407 --> 02:01:29,362
I already got a job here.

2700
02:01:29,407 --> 02:01:30,806
You know, I, uh,
deliver the mail.

2701
02:01:32,847 --> 02:01:37,363
Frank, we have the power
to take you out of prison.

2702
02:01:37,407 --> 02:01:38,999
You'd be placed
in the custody of the FBI

2703
02:01:39,047 --> 02:01:41,083
where you'd serve out
the remainder of your sentence

2704
02:01:41,127 --> 02:01:42,765
as an employee
of the federal government.

2705
02:01:45,327 --> 02:01:47,318
Under whose custody?

2706
02:01:53,207 --> 02:01:55,641
(<i>phone ringing</i>)

2707
02:01:55,687 --> 02:01:58,247
Hi. L-I'm Frank Abagnale.

2708
02:01:58,287 --> 02:02:00,642
I'm supposed to start work
here today.

2709
02:02:00,687 --> 02:02:03,155
It's a tour company
operating out of the BVI.

2710
02:02:03,207 --> 02:02:05,323
Sir, Mr. Abagnale is here.

2711
02:02:05,367 --> 02:02:06,720
I'm going to call you back.

2712
02:02:16,327 --> 02:02:19,080
(<i>melancholy melody playing</i>)

2713
02:02:35,767 --> 02:02:37,644
Hello, Carl.

2714
02:02:37,687 --> 02:02:39,245
Welcome to the FBI.

2715
02:02:39,287 --> 02:02:41,243
I'll show you
where you're working.

2716
02:02:48,327 --> 02:02:51,603
Carl... how long
do I have to work here?

2717
02:02:51,647 --> 02:02:54,241
It's 8:15 in the morning
to 5:00 in the afternoon.

2718
02:02:54,287 --> 02:02:56,164
45 minutes for lunch.

2719
02:02:56,207 --> 02:02:58,084
No, I...

2720
02:02:58,127 --> 02:03:00,277
I mean, how long?

2721
02:03:02,007 --> 02:03:04,077
Every day.

2722
02:03:04,127 --> 02:03:06,197
Every day, Frank,
till we let you go.

2723
02:03:55,967 --> 02:03:58,003
- (<i>tapping</i>)
- Yeah.

2724
02:03:58,047 --> 02:04:00,880
- Hey, Carl.
- Hi.

2725
02:04:00,927 --> 02:04:03,157
How you doing?

2726
02:04:03,207 --> 02:04:04,560
It's not a good time, Frank.

2727
02:04:04,607 --> 02:04:06,484
I'm clearing my desk
for the weekend.

2728
02:04:09,367 --> 02:04:12,120
Carl, you mind if I come
to work with you tomorrow?

2729
02:04:12,167 --> 02:04:14,123
Tomorrow is Saturday.

2730
02:04:14,167 --> 02:04:16,123
I'm flying to Chicago
to see my daughter.

2731
02:04:16,167 --> 02:04:17,680
I'll be back to work on Monday.

2732
02:04:17,727 --> 02:04:18,796
You're going to see Grace, huh?

2733
02:04:18,847 --> 02:04:20,360
Well, that's the plan.

2734
02:04:22,847 --> 02:04:23,836
(<i>heavy sigh</i>)

2735
02:04:23,887 --> 02:04:26,037
So what should I do till Monday?

2736
02:04:26,087 --> 02:04:27,725
I'm sorry, kid,
I can't help you there.

2737
02:04:27,767 --> 02:04:28,756
Excuse me.

2738
02:04:31,647 --> 02:04:35,276
(<i>phone rings</i>)

2739
02:04:35,327 --> 02:04:37,602
This is Hanratty.

2740
02:04:37,647 --> 02:04:39,558
Oh, yeah, put him on.

2741
02:04:47,247 --> 02:04:49,124
Mr. Sawyer.

2742
02:04:49,167 --> 02:04:50,919
How are you?

2743
02:04:50,967 --> 02:04:52,878
I have a half a dozen
more checks

2744
02:04:52,927 --> 02:04:54,918
on that tour operator
at the BVI.

2745
02:05:01,727 --> 02:05:03,638
(<i>laughs quietly</i>)

2746
02:05:16,687 --> 02:05:18,598
(<i>opens and shuts drawer</i>)

2747
02:05:26,727 --> 02:05:29,321
WOMAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
American Airlines 355

2748
02:05:29,367 --> 02:05:31,642
serving Chicago
and San Francisco

2749
02:05:31,687 --> 02:05:33,279
is now open
for passenger check-in.

2750
02:05:33,327 --> 02:05:36,478
How'd you do it, Frank?

2751
02:05:36,527 --> 02:05:39,644
How'd you pass the bar
in Louisiana?

2752
02:05:39,687 --> 02:05:41,996
What are you doing here?

2753
02:05:42,047 --> 02:05:44,038
Listen...

2754
02:05:44,087 --> 02:05:46,078
I'm sorry I put you
through all this.

2755
02:05:46,127 --> 02:05:48,925
You go back to Europe, you're
gonna die in Perpignan Prison.

2756
02:05:48,967 --> 02:05:50,480
You try to run
here in the States

2757
02:05:50,527 --> 02:05:52,597
we'll send you
back to Atlanta for 50 years.

2758
02:05:52,647 --> 02:05:55,844
I know that.

2759
02:05:55,887 --> 02:05:58,242
I spent four years trying
to arrange your release.

2760
02:05:58,287 --> 02:05:59,959
Had to convince my bosses
at the FBI

2761
02:06:00,007 --> 02:06:02,202
and the Attorney General
of the United States

2762
02:06:02,247 --> 02:06:03,157
you wouldn't run.

2763
02:06:03,207 --> 02:06:05,960
Why'd you do it?

2764
02:06:06,007 --> 02:06:07,360
You're just a kid.

2765
02:06:07,407 --> 02:06:09,125
I'm not your kid.

2766
02:06:09,167 --> 02:06:11,442
You said you were
going to Chicago.

2767
02:06:11,487 --> 02:06:13,318
My daughter can't see me
this weekend.

2768
02:06:13,367 --> 02:06:15,244
She's going skiing.

2769
02:06:15,287 --> 02:06:16,845
You said she was four years old.

2770
02:06:16,887 --> 02:06:17,922
You're lying.

2771
02:06:17,967 --> 02:06:19,480
She was four when I left.

2772
02:06:19,527 --> 02:06:20,846
Now she's 15.

2773
02:06:20,887 --> 02:06:23,924
My wife's been remarried
for 11 years.

2774
02:06:23,967 --> 02:06:26,117
I see Grace every now and again.

2775
02:06:26,167 --> 02:06:28,044
I don't understand.

2776
02:06:28,087 --> 02:06:29,964
Sure you do.

2777
02:06:30,007 --> 02:06:32,567
Sometimes it's easier
living the lie.

2778
02:06:35,887 --> 02:06:38,720
I'm going to let you
fly tonight, Frank.

2779
02:06:38,767 --> 02:06:40,564
I'm not even going
to try to stop you.

2780
02:06:40,607 --> 02:06:42,837
That's 'cause I know
you'll be back on Monday.

2781
02:06:42,887 --> 02:06:46,038
Yeah? How do you know
I'll come back?

2782
02:06:46,087 --> 02:06:48,681
(<i>chuckles quietly</i>)

2783
02:06:48,727 --> 02:06:50,843
Look.

2784
02:06:50,887 --> 02:06:52,718
Frank...

2785
02:06:52,767 --> 02:06:54,962
nobody's chasing you.

2786
02:06:55,007 --> 02:06:58,317
WOMAN (<i>over P.A.</i>):
American Airlines flight 131

2787
02:06:58,367 --> 02:07:01,120
to Pittsburgh
is now ready for boarding.

2788
02:07:01,167 --> 02:07:05,763
Passengers with boarding passes,
please proceed to Gate 23A.

2789
02:07:12,647 --> 02:07:14,239
Okay.

2790
02:07:14,287 --> 02:07:16,437
Alice, has he still not called?

2791
02:07:16,487 --> 02:07:18,398
No, he hasn't.

2792
02:07:27,967 --> 02:07:30,527
HANRATTY:
<i>Good morning.</i>

2793
02:07:30,567 --> 02:07:32,523
I've, uh, called this meeting
to discuss

2794
02:07:32,567 --> 02:07:34,762
a new type of check fraud
and counterfeiting

2795
02:07:34,807 --> 02:07:37,116
which the unsub is washing
and altering checks

2796
02:07:37,167 --> 02:07:39,044
then passing them
throughout Arizona.

2797
02:07:39,087 --> 02:07:43,046
(<i>panting</i>)

2798
02:07:43,087 --> 02:07:44,566
This unsub is a big dog

2799
02:07:44,607 --> 02:07:46,677
passing checks
as large as five figures.

2800
02:07:46,727 --> 02:07:48,445
(<i>door opening</i>)

2801
02:07:49,887 --> 02:07:52,720
Sorry I'm late.

2802
02:07:52,767 --> 02:07:54,678
Sorry.

2803
02:07:58,207 --> 02:08:01,483
We have a recovered check
on Agent Reiter's desk.

2804
02:08:01,527 --> 02:08:03,438
Why don't we step out
to the bullpen?

2805
02:08:07,607 --> 02:08:11,361
There's impressions
on every line.

2806
02:08:11,407 --> 02:08:15,002
Looks like the original amount
was for $60.

2807
02:08:18,567 --> 02:08:19,761
Mind if I take a look?

2808
02:08:23,127 --> 02:08:26,005
Cashed in Flagstaff a week ago.

2809
02:08:27,767 --> 02:08:30,565
Cost the bank $16,000.

2810
02:08:30,607 --> 02:08:32,484
It's a real check.

2811
02:08:32,527 --> 02:08:34,438
Yeah.

2812
02:08:34,487 --> 02:08:35,636
Yeah. It's been washed.

2813
02:08:35,687 --> 02:08:37,564
The only thing original
is the signature.

2814
02:08:37,607 --> 02:08:39,359
But it's perfect, Carl.
I mean...

2815
02:08:39,407 --> 02:08:41,602
I mean, this isn't hydrochloride
or bleach.

2816
02:08:41,647 --> 02:08:43,842
No.

2817
02:08:43,887 --> 02:08:45,525
Something new.

2818
02:08:45,567 --> 02:08:47,523
Maybe a nail polish remover
where the acetone

2819
02:08:47,567 --> 02:08:49,444
removes the ink
that's not been printed?

2820
02:08:53,327 --> 02:08:56,160
How did you do it, Frank?

2821
02:08:56,207 --> 02:08:59,085
How did you cheat
on the bar exam in Louisiana?

2822
02:09:04,287 --> 02:09:07,359
I didn't cheat.

2823
02:09:07,407 --> 02:09:10,877
I studied for two weeks
and I passed.

2824
02:09:11,927 --> 02:09:14,122
Is that the truth, Frank?

2825
02:09:14,167 --> 02:09:16,317
Is that the truth?

2826
02:09:16,367 --> 02:09:18,756
I'll bet this guy steals checks
out of mailboxes.

2827
02:09:18,807 --> 02:09:21,241
He washes off their names
and he puts on his own.

2828
02:09:23,007 --> 02:09:25,157
You're saying that he's a local?

2829
02:09:25,207 --> 02:09:26,435
Well, if it were me, you know

2830
02:09:26,487 --> 02:09:28,682
I'd call the bank first,
I'd check out the balance...

2831
02:09:28,727 --> 02:09:30,285
Make sure there's enough money
in there

2832
02:09:30,327 --> 02:09:31,476
to make it worth your while.

2833
02:09:31,527 --> 02:09:32,596
Exactly.

2834
02:09:32,647 --> 02:09:34,558
You know, Carl, I think
this guy's pretty smart.

2835
02:09:34,607 --> 02:09:36,165
I guess all we have to do now
is catch him.

2836
02:09:36,207 --> 02:09:37,640
We'll start first thing
in the morning.

2837
02:09:37,687 --> 02:09:39,120
We'll run the name
Eric Anthony Feeders.

2838
02:09:39,167 --> 02:09:40,316
In Nevada, Arizona, California.

2839
02:09:40,367 --> 02:09:42,198
Frank Abagnale, Jr. Has
been married for 26 years.

2840
02:09:42,247 --> 02:09:44,363
He has three sons and lives
a quiet life in the midwest.

2841
02:09:44,407 --> 02:09:47,001
Since his release
from prison in 1974,

2842
02:09:47,047 --> 02:09:51,598
Frank has helped the FBI capture
some of the world's most elusive

2843
02:09:51,647 --> 02:09:53,797
check forgers
and counterfeiters

2844
02:09:53,847 --> 02:09:57,840
and is considered one of the
world's foremost authorities

2845
02:09:57,887 --> 02:09:59,718
on bank fraud and forgery.

2846
02:09:59,767 --> 02:10:03,396
Frank has also designed many
of the secure checks

2847
02:10:03,447 --> 02:10:07,281
that banks and Fortune 500
companies use every day.

2848
02:10:08,287 --> 02:10:10,118
For his services,
these companies pay

2849
02:10:10,167 --> 02:10:12,601
Frank Abagnale, Jr.
Millions of dollars a year.

2850
02:10:13,687 --> 02:10:18,602
Frank and Carl remain close
friends to this day.

2851
02:14:51,767 --> 02:14:54,645
(<i>music ends</i>)

